idea to me and what

00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:14.260 align:middle line:84%
it means to be a modern
domesticated human?

00:01:14.260 --> 00:01:15.850 align:middle line:90%
How do we get here really?

00:01:15.850 --> 00:01:19.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, I think the easiest way
to put it in context for people

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:22.320 align:middle line:84%
is thinking about dogs
and what dogs are.

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:24.160 align:middle line:84%
So all of us are
familiar with dogs.

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:25.900 align:middle line:84%
We've all lived in
and amongst dogs,

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:27.940 align:middle line:84%
even if we're not dog
lovers or dog owners.

00:01:27.940 --> 00:01:30.190 align:middle line:84%
We know lots of
dogs as individuals.

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:33.370 align:middle line:84%
Every single one of them
biologically is a gray wolf.

00:01:33.370 --> 00:01:35.140 align:middle line:84%
They're not related
to gray wolves,

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:37.240 align:middle line:90%
they actually are gray wolves.

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:38.740 align:middle line:84%
So some of the
breeds you can really

00:01:38.740 --> 00:01:40.870 align:middle line:84%
see that it's easy to
understand if we see like any

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:42.540 align:middle line:84%
of the Alaskan sled
dog-type breeds

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:44.790 align:middle line:84%
or we see even a German
shepherd, you can look at that

00:01:44.790 --> 00:01:46.040 align:middle line:90%
and go I see the wolf in that.

00:01:46.040 --> 00:01:49.480 align:middle line:84%
But you start to get down
to a Shih Tzu, or a pitbull,

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:52.570 align:middle line:84%
or a little terrier, and
you don't see the gray wolf

00:01:52.570 --> 00:01:56.190 align:middle line:84%
anymore, you see that
domestication has changed them.

00:01:56.190 --> 00:02:00.500 align:middle line:84%
So the great wolf is Canis
lupus and the domesticated dog

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:04.210 align:middle line:84%
is Canis lupus familiaris and
we add that trinomial part,

00:02:04.210 --> 00:02:06.970 align:middle line:84%
that last epithet to
its name to designate

00:02:06.970 --> 00:02:08.530 align:middle line:90%
that it's been domesticated.

00:02:08.530 --> 00:02:10.900 align:middle line:84%
So you can see that as
something's moved away

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:14.140 align:middle line:84%
from wild nature, and
its diet has changed,

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:16.660 align:middle line:84%
and its environmental
conditions are changed,

00:02:16.660 --> 00:02:20.320 align:middle line:84%
and most importantly, probably,
sexual selection becomes

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:21.310 align:middle line:90%
a factor.

00:02:21.310 --> 00:02:23.230 align:middle line:84%
We think a lot about
natural selection,

00:02:23.230 --> 00:02:24.850 align:middle line:90%
how the environment shapes us.

00:02:24.850 --> 00:02:27.760 align:middle line:84%
What we forget is the
incredible power wielded usually

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:32.230 align:middle line:84%
by females of a species to
select mates that will drive

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:34.160 align:middle line:90%
radical changes in phenotypes.

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:35.890 align:middle line:84%
So you look at some
of the bird species,

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:37.610 align:middle line:84%
let's say, in the
Amazon and you think

00:02:37.610 --> 00:02:41.680 align:middle line:84%
how did natural selection
choose these radical colors

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:42.730 align:middle line:90%
and feather designs?

00:02:42.730 --> 00:02:44.813 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's not-- that's
not natural selection, not

00:02:44.813 --> 00:02:48.130 align:middle line:84%
the environment, that's
selection by females of mates.

00:02:48.130 --> 00:02:51.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, with domestication, we
get into artificial selection.

00:02:51.850 --> 00:02:54.230 align:middle line:90%
So we change the environment.

00:02:54.230 --> 00:02:55.880 align:middle line:84%
So it's no longer
natural selection,

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:57.640 align:middle line:84%
it's not the
environmental pressure,

00:02:57.640 --> 00:02:59.380 align:middle line:84%
and we become the
sexual selectors,

00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:00.280 align:middle line:90%
who we want to breed.

00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:03.580 align:middle line:84%
And, over time, we can in
actually a fairly short period

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:05.530 align:middle line:84%
of biological time--
we can take a gray wolf

00:03:05.530 --> 00:03:07.360 align:middle line:90%
and turn it to a chihuahua.

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:09.130 align:middle line:84%
We've done that with
a lot of species.

00:03:09.130 --> 00:03:11.250 align:middle line:84%
We've done that with cows,
and sheeps, and goats,

00:03:11.250 --> 00:03:13.000 align:middle line:84%
and we've done that
with a host of plants.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.830 align:middle line:84%
We're working on mushrooms,
and bacteria, and algaes,

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:18.430 align:middle line:84%
and all these things right
now, domesticating the world.

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:19.400 align:middle line:90%
In the process--

00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:21.948 align:middle line:84%
I don't think we ever set out
to domesticate ourselves--

00:03:21.948 --> 00:03:23.740 align:middle line:84%
but, in the process,
we did, inadvertently,

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:25.483 align:middle line:90%
domesticate ourselves.

00:03:25.483 --> 00:03:28.150 align:middle line:84%
It's important to understand the
timeline that this has happened

00:03:28.150 --> 00:03:29.710 align:middle line:90%
in because human beings--

00:03:29.710 --> 00:03:31.840 align:middle line:84%
we get new archeological
evidence all the time.

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:35.290 align:middle line:84%
And now genomics and
genetics has shown us--

00:03:35.290 --> 00:03:37.810 align:middle line:84%
we're able to peer a little
bit deeper into our origins.

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:40.930 align:middle line:84%
But we know that we're at least,
in our current form-- we're

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:43.470 align:middle line:84%
something like
300,000 years old.

00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:45.700 align:middle line:84%
All right, we've been
around for $300,000 years

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:47.560 align:middle line:90%
as modern humans.

00:03:47.560 --> 00:03:52.900 align:middle line:84%
But humans as a genus, genus
Homo, goes back a lot farther

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:54.850 align:middle line:84%
and all of us were
hunter-gatherers.

00:03:54.850 --> 00:03:56.550 align:middle line:90%
That's our wild type.

00:03:56.550 --> 00:03:58.300 align:middle line:84%
Most of us only interact
with human beings

00:03:58.300 --> 00:03:59.950 align:middle line:90%
of the domestic type.

00:03:59.950 --> 00:04:03.820 align:middle line:84%
But the wild type
hunts and gathers.

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:05.860 align:middle line:84%
It's something like
10,000 years ago,

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:09.160 align:middle line:84%
some would say 14,000 years
ago, 11,000 years ago.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:11.020 align:middle line:84%
Something between
10,000 and 14,000 years

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:14.380 align:middle line:84%
ago, human beings started
in the Fertile Crescent

00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:16.240 align:middle line:90%
started to plant things.

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:19.579 align:middle line:84%
We started-- we went from this
idea of tending to the wild--

00:04:19.579 --> 00:04:22.780 align:middle line:84%
and this is not a like surviving
hand-to-mouth kind of a thing.

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:25.630 align:middle line:84%
People had gotten very good
at getting food resources out

00:04:25.630 --> 00:04:28.700 align:middle line:84%
of their environment
and also interacting

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:30.700 align:middle line:84%
with the environment to
make it more productive.

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:31.750 align:middle line:90%
We tended the wild.

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:34.610 align:middle line:84%
We were gardeners of
the wild landscape.

00:04:34.610 --> 00:04:37.450 align:middle line:84%
But this idea to start
planting starts around 10,000

00:04:37.450 --> 00:04:38.920 align:middle line:90%
to 14,000 years ago.

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:43.090 align:middle line:84%
And very quickly we shift away
from being hunter-gatherers

00:04:43.090 --> 00:04:47.740 align:middle line:84%
in that area of the
world to being domestic,

00:04:47.740 --> 00:04:51.850 align:middle line:84%
to starting-- going away from
this idea of annual migration

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:54.520 align:middle line:84%
routes through our
range, where we would

00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:57.670 align:middle line:84%
go from our sort of winter
camp to our spring camp

00:04:57.670 --> 00:05:00.280 align:middle line:84%
to our summer camp, following
migrations of animals,

00:05:00.280 --> 00:05:02.050 align:middle line:84%
following the
ripening of plants,

00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:05.100 align:middle line:84%
getting away from insects like
mosquitos and things like.

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:07.600 align:middle line:84%
You learn, OK, in the summer,
we don't want to be down here.

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:08.870 align:middle line:90%
We're going to go up here.

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:10.287 align:middle line:84%
But once we start
planting, now we

00:05:10.287 --> 00:05:12.730 align:middle line:90%
need to kind of guard that area.

00:05:12.730 --> 00:05:13.720 align:middle line:90%
We need to weed it.

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:14.938 align:middle line:90%
We need to till it.

00:05:14.938 --> 00:05:16.480 align:middle line:84%
We need to keep
animals away from it.

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:19.480 align:middle line:84%
So people start to settle down
and this is the first time

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:21.373 align:middle line:90%
that we become sedentary.

00:05:21.373 --> 00:05:23.290 align:middle line:84%
Because prior to that,
we're not of the house.

00:05:23.290 --> 00:05:25.930 align:middle line:84%
Like you said, domestication
means "of the household."

00:05:25.930 --> 00:05:27.100 align:middle line:90%
We weren't of the house.

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:30.310 align:middle line:84%
We might have been of the
tent because we'd bring things

00:05:30.310 --> 00:05:33.850 align:middle line:84%
with us, but for the first time
people start settling down.

00:05:33.850 --> 00:05:37.580 align:middle line:84%
Very quickly, shockingly fast
out of that starts to emerge.

00:05:37.580 --> 00:05:38.710 align:middle line:90%
the city-states.

00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:40.690 align:middle line:84%
About 6,000, 7,000 years
ago we start seeing

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:42.700 align:middle line:90%
the first city-states emerge.

00:05:42.700 --> 00:05:45.880 align:middle line:84%
And what we have now
is enough surplus food

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:48.550 align:middle line:84%
to create an environment where
you can have a class of people

00:05:48.550 --> 00:05:51.430 align:middle line:84%
who can sit at the top and
not have to forage anymore,

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:52.698 align:middle line:90%
not have to hunt anymore.

00:05:52.698 --> 00:05:54.490 align:middle line:84%
In a hunter-gatherer
community, everybody's

00:05:54.490 --> 00:05:58.450 align:middle line:84%
like a sovereign individual
and it's an egalitarian system,

00:05:58.450 --> 00:06:02.170 align:middle line:84%
everyone does overlapping
jobs to make sure

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:03.250 align:middle line:90%
that everyone's fed.

00:06:03.250 --> 00:06:05.320 align:middle line:84%
Everybody forages,
everybody hunts.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:07.810 align:middle line:84%
The chief does and the
runt of the litter does.

00:06:07.810 --> 00:06:10.930 align:middle line:84%
Everybody participates
equally and together.

00:06:10.930 --> 00:06:12.700 align:middle line:84%
But now you have
this system where,

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:14.920 align:middle line:84%
through growing
grains primarily.

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:16.830 align:middle line:84%
In Mesopotamia we're
talking about wheat.

00:06:16.830 --> 00:06:18.580 align:middle line:84%
But if we get over to
Asia, another center

00:06:18.580 --> 00:06:20.710 align:middle line:84%
of domestication, we're
talking about rice.

00:06:20.710 --> 00:06:22.397 align:middle line:84%
If we go to-- over
to Mesoamerica,

00:06:22.397 --> 00:06:23.980 align:middle line:84%
we see another center
of domestication

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:26.290 align:middle line:84%
that arises later
based around maize,

00:06:26.290 --> 00:06:27.757 align:middle line:90%
or what we now call corn.

00:06:27.757 --> 00:06:29.590 align:middle line:84%
So we have several
centers of domestication,

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:32.200 align:middle line:84%
but they tend to focus
on growing up grass.

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:34.940 align:middle line:84%
So all those plants I just
mentioned wheat, barley

00:06:34.940 --> 00:06:38.940 align:middle line:84%
is another one, rice, corn,
those are all grasses.

00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:42.430 align:middle line:84%
They're seeds we call grains
and we can produce surplus food

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:43.230 align:middle line:90%
by doing that.

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:46.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is the first time
human beings have more food

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:47.440 align:middle line:90%
than they can eat.

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:52.270 align:middle line:84%
Hunter-gatherers tend to have
this sort of daily subsistence

00:06:52.270 --> 00:06:53.530 align:middle line:90%
or weekly subsistence.

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:56.500 align:middle line:84%
It's like we harvest
enough for what we need

00:06:56.500 --> 00:06:58.960 align:middle line:84%
and, as it runs down, we
go out we get more of it.

00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:01.970 align:middle line:84%
The hunters go out when the meat
resource starts to be depleted.

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:04.490 align:middle line:84%
The foragers go out when
the plant resource--

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:07.450 align:middle line:84%
some is stored-- but lots of
it's just sort of eaten up.

00:07:07.450 --> 00:07:10.420 align:middle line:84%
But for the first time now we
have all this surplus grain

00:07:10.420 --> 00:07:12.510 align:middle line:90%
and now we can feed more people.

00:07:12.510 --> 00:07:14.770 align:middle line:84%
So immediately what happens
is the population starts

00:07:14.770 --> 00:07:17.560 align:middle line:84%
to grow because people are
made out of-- turns out

00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:18.758 align:middle line:90%
we're made out of food.

00:07:18.758 --> 00:07:20.800 align:middle line:84%
And that's the thing that
I think a lot of people

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:21.600 align:middle line:90%
don't understand.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:23.830 align:middle line:84%
They talk about and
think about how we

00:07:23.830 --> 00:07:25.780 align:middle line:90%
deal with a population problem.

00:07:25.780 --> 00:07:28.700 align:middle line:84%
If you keep adding surplus
food into any population,

00:07:28.700 --> 00:07:31.510 align:middle line:84%
you'll have a population
problem, barring that you

00:07:31.510 --> 00:07:33.370 align:middle line:90%
somehow sterilize individuals.

00:07:33.370 --> 00:07:35.680 align:middle line:84%
I mean, people will
continue to reproduce

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:39.340 align:middle line:84%
because there's enough surplus
carbon to make more people.

00:07:39.340 --> 00:07:41.290 align:middle line:84%
And so you start to
have people settle down

00:07:41.290 --> 00:07:44.500 align:middle line:84%
and then quickly they
start to grow and multiply.

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:46.570 align:middle line:84%
And then you start to
get a stratified society

00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:49.595 align:middle line:84%
because you need somebody to
sort of watch over the grain.

00:07:49.595 --> 00:07:51.220 align:middle line:84%
And then you need
somebody to determine

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:52.667 align:middle line:90%
how to distribute the grain.

00:07:52.667 --> 00:07:54.750 align:middle line:84%
And then you got to start
having rules about that.

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:56.860 align:middle line:84%
So now you've got to have sort
of a legal class and, well,

00:07:56.860 --> 00:07:57.730 align:middle line:90%
how do you enforce that?

00:07:57.730 --> 00:07:59.290 align:middle line:84%
Well, now you need
an enforcement class?

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:00.707 align:middle line:84%
Well, who sits on
the top of that?

00:08:00.707 --> 00:08:03.880 align:middle line:84%
You start to quickly develop a
hierarchical system, which is

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:06.110 align:middle line:90%
not our natural way of living.

00:08:06.110 --> 00:08:08.680 align:middle line:84%
So in the same way that
for dogs, let's say--

00:08:08.680 --> 00:08:10.720 align:middle line:84%
for dogs interacting in
a household environment

00:08:10.720 --> 00:08:12.700 align:middle line:90%
like-- a wolf is a pack animal.

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:14.920 align:middle line:84%
We say lone wolf sometimes,
but there aren't really

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:15.740 align:middle line:90%
lone wolves.

00:08:15.740 --> 00:08:18.370 align:middle line:84%
There might be lone
coyotes, but wolves no.

00:08:18.370 --> 00:08:19.570 align:middle line:90%
They are a pack animal.

00:08:19.570 --> 00:08:20.740 align:middle line:90%
They're a social animal.

00:08:20.740 --> 00:08:22.840 align:middle line:84%
This idea of a dog
living alone in a house

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:25.960 align:middle line:84%
with a couple of people,
not normal for dogs.

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:28.540 align:middle line:84%
Can work, but not normal
for dogs biologically.

00:08:28.540 --> 00:08:30.220 align:middle line:84%
That's not their
biological norm.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:32.830 align:middle line:84%
Living in a hierarchical
structure where

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:35.919 align:middle line:84%
you have a ruling class, and
a policing and military class,

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:38.257 align:middle line:84%
and a educational
class, and then you

00:08:38.257 --> 00:08:40.090 align:middle line:84%
get down to a sort of
a worker class, that's

00:08:40.090 --> 00:08:41.799 align:middle line:90%
not our natural way of being.

00:08:41.799 --> 00:08:44.150 align:middle line:84%
We can make it work
to some degree,

00:08:44.150 --> 00:08:46.180 align:middle line:84%
but that's not our
biological norm.

00:08:46.180 --> 00:08:48.070 align:middle line:84%
But that's what came
out of domestication.

00:08:48.070 --> 00:08:49.670 align:middle line:84%
This all starts like
10,000 years ago.

00:08:49.670 --> 00:08:51.212 align:middle line:84%
So, again, if we
took this timeline--

00:08:51.212 --> 00:08:56.380 align:middle line:84%
here's 300,000 years and this
whole time we hunt and gather

00:08:56.380 --> 00:08:59.045 align:middle line:90%
and then 10,000 years ago--

00:08:59.045 --> 00:09:00.670 align:middle line:84%
and it's not like
10,000 years ago-- we

00:09:00.670 --> 00:09:04.120 align:middle line:84%
call this thing the Neolithic
Revolution, the first planting,

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:06.760 align:middle line:84%
it makes it sound like it just
caught fire and went around

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:07.120 align:middle line:90%
the world.

00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:09.662 align:middle line:84%
I would point out that this is
not even a complete revolution

00:09:09.662 --> 00:09:10.678 align:middle line:90%
yet.

00:09:10.678 --> 00:09:12.220 align:middle line:84%
There are people
all around the world

00:09:12.220 --> 00:09:13.540 align:middle line:90%
still hunting and gathering.

00:09:13.540 --> 00:09:14.998 align:middle line:84%
And I don't mean
people like myself

00:09:14.998 --> 00:09:16.930 align:middle line:84%
who've taken it on
as a modern practice,

00:09:16.930 --> 00:09:19.000 align:middle line:84%
but I mean true
subsistence hunters

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.700 align:middle line:84%
and gatherers like we would
find some in the Amazon, what

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:23.103 align:middle line:90%
we call the uncontacted tribes.

00:09:23.103 --> 00:09:24.520 align:middle line:84%
We'd find some in
New Guinea, we'd

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:26.890 align:middle line:84%
find some in Africa,
that have not

00:09:26.890 --> 00:09:29.620 align:middle line:84%
bought into the
agricultural model yet.

00:09:29.620 --> 00:09:30.680 align:middle line:90%
We're very close.

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:35.260 align:middle line:84%
And it's like-- it hurts to
say it, but in my lifetime,

00:09:35.260 --> 00:09:37.480 align:middle line:84%
they'll probably
be no more true,

00:09:37.480 --> 00:09:39.970 align:middle line:84%
wild subsistence lineages
left in the world.

00:09:39.970 --> 00:09:41.470 align:middle line:84%
I mean they're all
shifting over now

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:44.890 align:middle line:84%
as they're drawn into or
voluntarily come into what

00:09:44.890 --> 00:09:46.420 align:middle line:90%
we call the modern world.

00:09:46.420 --> 00:09:47.950 align:middle line:84%
But it's not like
10,000 years ago

00:09:47.950 --> 00:09:50.620 align:middle line:84%
everybody on the planet
switched to this, just in just

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:51.917 align:middle line:90%
in this one area.

00:09:51.917 --> 00:09:53.500 align:middle line:84%
And then that started
to spread there,

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:56.020 align:middle line:84%
and then crops up in Peru,
it crops up in Mexico,

00:09:56.020 --> 00:09:58.750 align:middle line:84%
it crops up in Asia, and you
get these domestication centers.

00:09:58.750 --> 00:10:01.255 align:middle line:84%
Well, what they tend to
do is need more land.

00:10:01.255 --> 00:10:02.630 align:middle line:84%
They're growing
their population.

00:10:02.630 --> 00:10:04.650 align:middle line:84%
They go out, they conquest,
they take more land,

00:10:04.650 --> 00:10:08.790 align:middle line:84%
but this happens slowly and
we're not even fully there yet.

00:10:08.790 --> 00:10:10.350 align:middle line:84%
So when we look
at that timeline,

00:10:10.350 --> 00:10:11.940 align:middle line:84%
when did humans
get domesticated?

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:15.180 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's like right here
some humans did in this 300,000

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:18.600 align:middle line:84%
your timeline and then that's
not even all of them until--

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:19.980 align:middle line:90%
we're almost there.

00:10:19.980 --> 00:10:23.250 align:middle line:84%
It's basically happened
yesterday in biological terms.

00:10:23.250 --> 00:10:26.160 align:middle line:84%
We are not yet adapted
to living this way.

00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:28.860 align:middle line:84%
We don't really know
how to live this way.

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:30.480 align:middle line:84%
The pace of
technology is so fast

00:10:30.480 --> 00:10:33.690 align:middle line:84%
that our-- biologically we
can't stay up to speed with it.

00:10:33.690 --> 00:10:35.070 align:middle line:90%
We're trying, but we--

00:10:35.070 --> 00:10:37.320 align:middle line:90%
things keep changing.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:41.020 align:middle line:84%
We got domesticated and
didn't even realize it.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:42.780 align:middle line:84%
But unlike a dog,
we wear more of

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:47.130 align:middle line:84%
like an invisible kind of
collar and an invisible leash.

00:10:47.130 --> 00:10:50.340 align:middle line:84%
Because it's like an unseen
hand, where the dog knows

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:53.580 align:middle line:84%
you're the master, telling
it what it can and can't do,

00:10:53.580 --> 00:10:55.470 align:middle line:84%
setting the rules,
and feeding it.

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:57.630 align:middle line:84%
But we sort of
have like-- we have

00:10:57.630 --> 00:11:00.870 align:middle line:84%
a sense in our culture
of our freedom,

00:11:00.870 --> 00:11:03.660 align:middle line:84%
but we're much more
like free range cattle

00:11:03.660 --> 00:11:06.300 align:middle line:84%
than we are like
free human beings.

00:11:06.300 --> 00:11:08.760 align:middle line:84%
And so there is a
saying, the next step

00:11:08.760 --> 00:11:13.020 align:middle line:84%
after free range is in freedom,
it's the slaughterhouse.

00:11:13.020 --> 00:11:16.000 align:middle line:84%
We don't raise
ourselves for meat.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.730 align:middle line:90%
We don't eat people, thankfully.

00:11:17.730 --> 00:11:20.530 align:middle line:84%
But we certainly raise
ourselves for the labor force.

00:11:20.530 --> 00:11:22.230 align:middle line:90%
That's kind of what we do.

00:11:22.230 --> 00:11:25.410 align:middle line:84%
We live on like a human
factory farm in a way,

00:11:25.410 --> 00:11:28.937 align:middle line:84%
raised up for the labor force,
told that if we work hard

00:11:28.937 --> 00:11:30.270 align:middle line:90%
we'll have some kind of freedom.

00:11:30.270 --> 00:11:32.310 align:middle line:84%
But the thing is, we all
know as we become adults,

00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:34.310 align:middle line:84%
it's kind of like a trap
and that you can't ever

00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:35.350 align:middle line:90%
really get free.

00:11:35.350 --> 00:11:37.470 align:middle line:84%
It's more fair to
say we're free range.

00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:40.120 align:middle line:84%
So at this point,
human domestication

00:11:40.120 --> 00:11:43.260 align:middle line:84%
is 7 billion
people, most of whom

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:46.350 align:middle line:84%
live on like a giant
human factory farm.

00:11:46.350 --> 00:11:47.670 align:middle line:90%
In some places.

00:11:47.670 --> 00:11:49.560 align:middle line:90%
It's more like a CAFO.

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:50.997 align:middle line:90%
Some parts of the world--

00:11:50.997 --> 00:11:52.830 align:middle line:84%
sometimes we call that
the third world or we

00:11:52.830 --> 00:11:55.260 align:middle line:84%
call that the developing world,
where they're struggling.

00:11:55.260 --> 00:11:57.540 align:middle line:84%
It's much harder, there's
a lot less freedom to move.

00:11:57.540 --> 00:11:59.490 align:middle line:84%
And then some
places where we in--

00:11:59.490 --> 00:12:01.890 align:middle line:84%
like in the more
developed nations

00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:04.462 align:middle line:84%
where people have the sense
of all this economic freedom,

00:12:04.462 --> 00:12:06.420 align:middle line:84%
I'd say it's more like
a really nice free range

00:12:06.420 --> 00:12:08.420 align:middle line:84%
farm, the one you want
to see on the box of eggs

00:12:08.420 --> 00:12:11.880 align:middle line:84%
when you get them, the pasture
where we can move about freely,

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:13.990 align:middle line:84%
but we don't have
the true freedom

00:12:13.990 --> 00:12:15.490 align:middle line:84%
that hunter-gatherers
had and that's

00:12:15.490 --> 00:12:17.198 align:middle line:84%
the kind of freedom
most of us can't even

00:12:17.198 --> 00:12:18.960 align:middle line:90%
really imagine anymore.

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:21.870 align:middle line:84%
>> This comes, obviously,
with side effects.

00:12:21.870 --> 00:12:26.340 align:middle line:84%
You look at a pug dog and it
can hardly breathe, it's got--

00:12:26.340 --> 00:12:29.160 align:middle line:84%
it has issues where you look
at a certain dog that gets--

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:31.470 align:middle line:84%
always gets hip issues
or something and that's

00:12:31.470 --> 00:12:36.300 align:middle line:84%
because they're
genetically not pure.

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:37.680 align:middle line:84%
What are some of
the side effects

00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:39.638 align:middle line:84%
that the human species
are experiencing

00:12:39.638 --> 00:12:41.180 align:middle line:84%
because of this sort
of domestication

00:12:41.180 --> 00:12:42.630 align:middle line:90%
that you've explained?

00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:44.460 align:middle line:84%
>> It's funny, it's actually
because they are genetically

00:12:44.460 --> 00:12:45.260 align:middle line:90%
poor--

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:48.322 align:middle line:84%
I want to just kind of
reframe that just a little bit

00:12:48.322 --> 00:12:50.280 align:middle line:84%
because you start-- when
you start to use terms

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:52.363 align:middle line:84%
like genetic purity, it's
like, ooh, we're getting

00:12:52.363 --> 00:12:53.490 align:middle line:90%
into some sticky territory.

00:12:53.490 --> 00:12:56.560 align:middle line:84%
And it's led to some
weird places in the past.

00:12:56.560 --> 00:12:59.220 align:middle line:84%
When we talk about a
purebred dog, the dog that

00:12:59.220 --> 00:13:02.190 align:middle line:84%
comes with papers, the dog that
can get into the kennel club,

00:13:02.190 --> 00:13:05.130 align:middle line:84%
that's actually a very
genetically weak animal.

00:13:05.130 --> 00:13:07.960 align:middle line:84%
It's come from a very
restricted gene pool.

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:09.690 align:middle line:90%
So this is not a well--

00:13:09.690 --> 00:13:12.330 align:middle line:84%
this is not an animal with
a lot of room to adapt.

00:13:12.330 --> 00:13:14.580 align:middle line:84%
It can't go to this side of
the pool, the shallow side

00:13:14.580 --> 00:13:15.380 align:middle line:90%
or the deep side.

00:13:15.380 --> 00:13:17.430 align:middle line:90%
It's in the shallow side.

00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:20.013 align:middle line:84%
So if it was a German
shepherd, as you brought up,

00:13:20.013 --> 00:13:21.930 align:middle line:84%
and they're going to end
up with hip dysplasia

00:13:21.930 --> 00:13:24.030 align:middle line:84%
almost every time,
you just kind of know

00:13:24.030 --> 00:13:26.072 align:middle line:84%
what it's going to end up
with, or you brought up

00:13:26.072 --> 00:13:29.130 align:middle line:84%
pugs where they're their entire
face has been sort of crushed

00:13:29.130 --> 00:13:30.780 align:middle line:84%
forward, they can't
breathe anymore.

00:13:30.780 --> 00:13:33.342 align:middle line:84%
These are artifacts of
this sexual selection

00:13:33.342 --> 00:13:34.550 align:middle line:90%
we were talking about before.

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:40.080 align:middle line:84%
So somebody says I like a German
shepherd with hips that are

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:42.420 align:middle line:84%
lower than its shoulder
blades, let's say,

00:13:42.420 --> 00:13:45.330 align:middle line:84%
and over time if you look at
pictures of German shepherds 50

00:13:45.330 --> 00:13:46.980 align:middle line:84%
years ago, 60
years ago to today,

00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:48.830 align:middle line:84%
you'll see that
they've gotten that's--

00:13:48.830 --> 00:13:53.653 align:middle line:84%
that aesthetic that people
in the German shepherd

00:13:53.653 --> 00:13:54.570 align:middle line:90%
has been selected for.

00:13:54.570 --> 00:13:57.313 align:middle line:84%
Oh, this female has it and this
male has it, let's breed them.

00:13:57.313 --> 00:13:59.355 align:middle line:84%
Oh, now let's take puppies
and keep breeding that

00:13:59.355 --> 00:14:00.890 align:middle line:90%
and keep breeding that.

00:14:00.890 --> 00:14:03.390 align:middle line:84%
So as we've done that, we've
ended up with these animals who

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:05.700 align:middle line:84%
have all of these
artifacts, these

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:08.710 align:middle line:84%
features that actually
impact their health.

00:14:08.710 --> 00:14:10.350 align:middle line:84%
We're seeing that in
ourselves as well,

00:14:10.350 --> 00:14:12.990 align:middle line:84%
but we're actually way more
willy-nilly with our own

00:14:12.990 --> 00:14:14.730 align:middle line:90%
breeding than we are with--

00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:16.563 align:middle line:84%
and, again, this is
delicate territory.

00:14:16.563 --> 00:14:18.480 align:middle line:84%
We've seen the eugenics
programs that happened

00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:21.300 align:middle line:84%
and that we fought
a world war over.

00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:23.550 align:middle line:84%
It's not like we want to
bring in sort of a regulation

00:14:23.550 --> 00:14:25.650 align:middle line:84%
on how we breed,
but some of us can

00:14:25.650 --> 00:14:27.960 align:middle line:84%
be more thoughtful at an
individual level about what

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:28.950 align:middle line:90%
we're choosing.

00:14:28.950 --> 00:14:31.710 align:middle line:84%
What we've ended up with
is a lot of these artifacts

00:14:31.710 --> 00:14:33.450 align:middle line:90%
as well like--

00:14:33.450 --> 00:14:35.640 align:middle line:84%
it's now considered
quite normal for people

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:39.720 align:middle line:84%
to need dental work because
their teeth no longer fit

00:14:39.720 --> 00:14:40.870 align:middle line:90%
into their mouth.

00:14:40.870 --> 00:14:43.020 align:middle line:84%
This is something
that doesn't exist

00:14:43.020 --> 00:14:46.800 align:middle line:84%
in hunter-gatherer cultures
where they have lived there

00:14:46.800 --> 00:14:47.948 align:middle line:90%
intact traditional lifeway.

00:14:47.948 --> 00:14:49.740 align:middle line:84%
That's hard for people
to hear because what

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:52.860 align:middle line:84%
they see a lot of times on TV
are people whose lives have

00:14:52.860 --> 00:14:54.925 align:middle line:84%
been very-- we'll see a
hunter-gatherer group,

00:14:54.925 --> 00:14:57.300 align:middle line:84%
but they're actually living
on a lot of wheat, and sugar,

00:14:57.300 --> 00:14:58.950 align:middle line:84%
and corn, or
something like that.

00:14:58.950 --> 00:15:01.300 align:middle line:84%
The UN has brought in
a lot of Western foods,

00:15:01.300 --> 00:15:03.488 align:middle line:84%
their lifestyle has
changed, and now

00:15:03.488 --> 00:15:06.030 align:middle line:84%
they are the recipients of many
of these dental problems too.

00:15:06.030 --> 00:15:07.447 align:middle line:84%
But traditionally,
especially when

00:15:07.447 --> 00:15:09.110 align:middle line:84%
we look at our
fossil record, we see

00:15:09.110 --> 00:15:11.027 align:middle line:84%
that this idea of needing
braces for our teeth

00:15:11.027 --> 00:15:13.250 align:middle line:84%
to fit in our mouth,
that's like the pug who

00:15:13.250 --> 00:15:14.210 align:middle line:90%
can't breed anymore.

00:15:14.210 --> 00:15:15.425 align:middle line:90%
That's not natural to us.

00:15:15.425 --> 00:15:17.300 align:middle line:84%
In fact, if you go back
in the fossil record,

00:15:17.300 --> 00:15:19.092 align:middle line:84%
one of the things that's
really fascinating

00:15:19.092 --> 00:15:21.518 align:middle line:84%
is that when we see that early
domestication that happened

00:15:21.518 --> 00:15:23.310 align:middle line:84%
in the Fertile Crescent
I was talking about

00:15:23.310 --> 00:15:25.313 align:middle line:84%
is there was an immediate
reduction in height,

00:15:25.313 --> 00:15:27.230 align:middle line:84%
there was immediate
reduction in bone density.

00:15:27.230 --> 00:15:28.970 align:middle line:84%
We start to see
scarring on the bones,

00:15:28.970 --> 00:15:31.940 align:middle line:84%
we start to see impacts
of boom-bust cycles

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:32.790 align:middle line:90%
of agriculture.

00:15:32.790 --> 00:15:34.790 align:middle line:84%
So people have a year of
no food and then a year

00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:36.890 align:middle line:84%
of lots of food, whereas
hunter-gatherers have,

00:15:36.890 --> 00:15:39.350 align:middle line:84%
because they have so
many plant and animal

00:15:39.350 --> 00:15:42.140 align:middle line:84%
resources they can draw upon,
they have steady nutrition

00:15:42.140 --> 00:15:44.780 align:middle line:84%
but not so much in traditional
agricultural societies

00:15:44.780 --> 00:15:46.790 align:middle line:90%
where they would have droughts.

00:15:46.790 --> 00:15:49.430 align:middle line:84%
Droughts don't affect
hunter-gatherers so much.

00:15:49.430 --> 00:15:51.440 align:middle line:84%
you just-- the wild
plants still grow.

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:53.420 align:middle line:84%
And maybe this plant's
not as available,

00:15:53.420 --> 00:15:56.660 align:middle line:84%
but we know 40 other ones
that we can use in a pinch.

00:15:56.660 --> 00:15:59.360 align:middle line:84%
Whereas agriculturists put
all the eggs in one basket

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:01.670 align:middle line:84%
so to say or we say all
the seeds in one plot.

00:16:01.670 --> 00:16:04.220 align:middle line:84%
And if that doesn't
work out, now you're

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:05.930 align:middle line:84%
boiling your leather
belt for food

00:16:05.930 --> 00:16:07.350 align:middle line:84%
because you've got
nothing to eat.

00:16:07.350 --> 00:16:11.010 align:middle line:84%
So that will lead to
weak enamel in the teeth

00:16:11.010 --> 00:16:13.100 align:middle line:90%
and it'll lead to weak bones.

00:16:13.100 --> 00:16:16.220 align:middle line:84%
We actually see a brain
case size reduction

00:16:16.220 --> 00:16:17.580 align:middle line:90%
in the fossil record as well.

00:16:17.580 --> 00:16:20.122 align:middle line:84%
So there's some indication that
we might have actually become

00:16:20.122 --> 00:16:22.070 align:middle line:90%
somewhat less intelligent.

00:16:22.070 --> 00:16:24.230 align:middle line:84%
There is a tendency to
think of ourselves right now

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:26.660 align:middle line:84%
as the smartest
we have ever been.

00:16:26.660 --> 00:16:29.510 align:middle line:84%
I think that that's
really in question

00:16:29.510 --> 00:16:33.360 align:middle line:84%
because if we could go back
that 100,000, 200,000 years ago,

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:34.400 align:middle line:90%
these are humans.

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:36.920 align:middle line:84%
This is somebody-- you can run
them through a pilot school

00:16:36.920 --> 00:16:38.368 align:middle line:90%
and they could fly a jumbo jet.

00:16:38.368 --> 00:16:40.160 align:middle line:84%
We tend to think like,
oh, this is somebody

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:42.460 align:middle line:90%
dragging knuckles in the cave.

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:44.840 align:middle line:84%
No, these are humans
as intelligent as us

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:47.660 align:middle line:84%
but far more adapted
to the environment

00:16:47.660 --> 00:16:51.050 align:middle line:84%
far more integrated
into the environment

00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:52.400 align:middle line:90%
and actually healthier than us.

00:16:52.400 --> 00:16:55.310 align:middle line:84%
One of-- probably the
biggest takeaway from this

00:16:55.310 --> 00:16:58.730 align:middle line:84%
is that we have all of
these chronic diseases that

00:16:58.730 --> 00:17:02.330 align:middle line:84%
don't show up in people who
live a traditional lifeway

00:17:02.330 --> 00:17:03.560 align:middle line:90%
on the landscape.

00:17:03.560 --> 00:17:09.170 align:middle line:84%
That's things like cancer, heart
disease, diabetes, obesity.

00:17:09.170 --> 00:17:13.520 align:middle line:84%
So many of the things that
are headline news all the time

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:15.470 align:middle line:90%
weren't really serious problems.

00:17:15.470 --> 00:17:16.940 align:middle line:84%
It's not that they
never existed,

00:17:16.940 --> 00:17:19.069 align:middle line:84%
but they existed in
numbers that made

00:17:19.069 --> 00:17:20.780 align:middle line:90%
them like almost negligible.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:22.930 align:middle line:84%
And we're dealing
with a lot of this.

00:17:22.930 --> 00:17:24.589 align:middle line:84%
Now, there's benefits
to our lifestyle.

00:17:24.589 --> 00:17:26.589 align:middle line:84%
I'm not-- I don't mean
to act like there aren't.

00:17:26.589 --> 00:17:28.640 align:middle line:84%
And one of them is that
we have greater longevity

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:29.807 align:middle line:90%
and the other one would be--

00:17:29.807 --> 00:17:32.420 align:middle line:90%
I can think of two--

00:17:32.420 --> 00:17:35.270 align:middle line:84%
aside from all the comforts,
of course, we have comfort.

00:17:35.270 --> 00:17:37.580 align:middle line:84%
We no longer worry about like
I'm going to walk outside

00:17:37.580 --> 00:17:40.520 align:middle line:84%
and I have to think about
predators that might eat me.

00:17:40.520 --> 00:17:43.070 align:middle line:84%
That's an actual real
thing that people

00:17:43.070 --> 00:17:46.620 align:middle line:84%
deal with if they live out
in natural environments.

00:17:46.620 --> 00:17:51.140 align:middle line:84%
But the two main things that
we have are increased longevity

00:17:51.140 --> 00:17:56.153 align:middle line:84%
and we have much
less child mortality.

00:17:56.153 --> 00:17:58.070 align:middle line:84%
But I would like to
address those individually

00:17:58.070 --> 00:18:00.073 align:middle line:84%
because they sound
like, oh, well,

00:18:00.073 --> 00:18:01.490 align:middle line:84%
then that the
deal's sealed, we're

00:18:01.490 --> 00:18:02.810 align:middle line:90%
doing this agricultural thing.

00:18:02.810 --> 00:18:04.643 align:middle line:84%
We're going full
domestication because we're

00:18:04.643 --> 00:18:07.340 align:middle line:84%
going to live longer and our
kids are going to survive.

00:18:07.340 --> 00:18:09.130 align:middle line:90%
The normal-- this is--

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:10.970 align:middle line:84%
again, this is like
hard for people to hear,

00:18:10.970 --> 00:18:15.170 align:middle line:84%
but the normal mortality
rate for children

00:18:15.170 --> 00:18:18.440 align:middle line:90%
is something about like 50%.

00:18:18.440 --> 00:18:20.580 align:middle line:90%
That's just normal for humans.

00:18:20.580 --> 00:18:23.900 align:middle line:84%
This is normal for lots of
animals, lots of animals.

00:18:23.900 --> 00:18:25.850 align:middle line:90%
You look at an animal like--

00:18:25.850 --> 00:18:28.610 align:middle line:84%
you catch a fish and it's got
a roe sac and you're like, wow,

00:18:28.610 --> 00:18:30.770 align:middle line:90%
there's 30,000 eggs in there.

00:18:30.770 --> 00:18:31.970 align:middle line:90%
Why 30,000 eggs?

00:18:31.970 --> 00:18:34.160 align:middle line:84%
Because almost none of
those fertilized eggs

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:36.390 align:middle line:84%
will actually
survive to adulthood.

00:18:36.390 --> 00:18:39.170 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is free
cast out as many larva

00:18:39.170 --> 00:18:42.230 align:middle line:84%
as you can because
very few will make it.

00:18:42.230 --> 00:18:44.960 align:middle line:84%
Humans have a much different
strategy, of course.

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:46.460 align:middle line:84%
It takes a long
time to raise a kid.

00:18:46.460 --> 00:18:48.085 align:middle line:84%
It takes a tremendous
amount of effort.

00:18:48.085 --> 00:18:51.080 align:middle line:84%
They come out not very well
prepared for the environment.

00:18:51.080 --> 00:18:53.280 align:middle line:84%
So we have to put a
lot of investment in,

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:55.670 align:middle line:84%
but it was very normal
for kids to die.

00:18:55.670 --> 00:18:59.910 align:middle line:84%
The thing is that when you take
a high child mortality rate

00:18:59.910 --> 00:19:02.300 align:middle line:84%
and you try to create
an average lifespan,

00:19:02.300 --> 00:19:03.800 align:middle line:84%
it makes the average
life span sound

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:07.370 align:middle line:84%
a lot smaller than what a person
who is an adult would live to.

00:19:07.370 --> 00:19:09.650 align:middle line:84%
So you'll hear, oh, our
ancestors only lived to 30.

00:19:09.650 --> 00:19:11.960 align:middle line:84%
It's like, no,
that's ridiculous.

00:19:11.960 --> 00:19:14.240 align:middle line:84%
If you take out all of
this child mortality,

00:19:14.240 --> 00:19:16.863 align:middle line:84%
you start to see if you
make it to adulthood,

00:19:16.863 --> 00:19:19.280 align:middle line:84%
your chances are that you're
going to live a healthy, very

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:20.970 align:middle line:90%
long life.

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:24.440 align:middle line:84%
The other aspect and this came
from interviewing a person who

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:29.570 align:middle line:84%
researches archeological
grave sites

00:19:29.570 --> 00:19:31.550 align:middle line:84%
and she told me that
they can't really

00:19:31.550 --> 00:19:35.240 align:middle line:90%
date human bones past age 55.

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:36.650 align:middle line:84%
So what happens
is when you might

00:19:36.650 --> 00:19:41.550 align:middle line:84%
be looking at an 80-year-old
body, but you'll call it 55.

00:19:41.550 --> 00:19:46.310 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a
55-year-old maximum lifespan

00:19:46.310 --> 00:19:47.960 align:middle line:84%
and you take this
high child mortality,

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:49.850 align:middle line:84%
it makes it appear that
our ancestors didn't

00:19:49.850 --> 00:19:50.700 align:middle line:90%
live very long.

00:19:50.700 --> 00:19:52.580 align:middle line:84%
They had the same kind
of life spans as us,

00:19:52.580 --> 00:19:57.680 align:middle line:84%
but, on average, more
of us make it longer.

00:19:57.680 --> 00:20:00.550 align:middle line:90%
That's also true in zoos.

00:20:00.550 --> 00:20:04.510 align:middle line:84%
So if we take an animal from the
wild and we put it in a zoo--

00:20:04.510 --> 00:20:06.160 align:middle line:84%
if we took a deer,
for instance--

00:20:06.160 --> 00:20:09.680 align:middle line:84%
if you got a five, six,
seven-year-old deer here,

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:11.470 align:middle line:84%
that's incredible
because most of them

00:20:11.470 --> 00:20:13.260 align:middle line:84%
aren't going to
make it that long.

00:20:13.260 --> 00:20:15.740 align:middle line:84%
It's because the
environment's difficult,

00:20:15.740 --> 00:20:17.380 align:middle line:84%
there's a high
winter kill, there's

00:20:17.380 --> 00:20:20.290 align:middle line:84%
predation by people and
other animals, hunters

00:20:20.290 --> 00:20:21.585 align:middle line:90%
and other animals.

00:20:21.585 --> 00:20:23.210 align:middle line:84%
They don't typically
make it that long.

00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:25.002 align:middle line:84%
But if we put them in
a zoo with these kind

00:20:25.002 --> 00:20:27.370 align:middle line:84%
of ideal conditions,
soft conditions,

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:28.690 align:middle line:90%
they'll live a lot longer.

00:20:28.690 --> 00:20:30.280 align:middle line:84%
We do have to ask
ourselves would

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:34.270 align:middle line:84%
that deer prefer to live
in a zoo or live freely.

00:20:34.270 --> 00:20:38.260 align:middle line:84%
Would the average gorilla
prefer to be in an enclosure

00:20:38.260 --> 00:20:39.640 align:middle line:90%
or would it prefer to be free?

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:43.390 align:middle line:84%
If you told me that I can
be free on the landscape

00:20:43.390 --> 00:20:46.000 align:middle line:84%
and I was going to
live 10 less years

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000 align:middle line:84%
or I could live in
confinement but I

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.880 align:middle line:84%
could have 10 more years of
confinement and especially

00:20:51.880 --> 00:20:54.100 align:middle line:84%
if those last 10 were going
to be heavily drugged,

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:57.760 align:middle line:84%
and constant medical
problems, and pain, and all

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:00.330 align:middle line:84%
those kind of things, it's
like there might be ben--

00:21:00.330 --> 00:21:03.310 align:middle line:84%
that longevity might not
be a panacea, might not

00:21:03.310 --> 00:21:05.267 align:middle line:90%
be as great as it sounds.

00:21:05.267 --> 00:21:06.850 align:middle line:84%
The other thing with
child mortality--

00:21:06.850 --> 00:21:10.090 align:middle line:84%
this is a challenging one and I
want to be really upfront here.

00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:14.430 align:middle line:84%
I've experienced
reproductive grief myself.

00:21:14.430 --> 00:21:18.218 align:middle line:84%
I have lost nephews and
nieces to child mortality.

00:21:18.218 --> 00:21:19.760 align:middle line:84%
I have a lot of
friends who've lost--

00:21:19.760 --> 00:21:23.260 align:middle line:84%
like several friends who've
lost children from everything

00:21:23.260 --> 00:21:26.740 align:middle line:84%
from before they were
born, to the day they were

00:21:26.740 --> 00:21:29.240 align:middle line:84%
born to 30 days
late, even friends

00:21:29.240 --> 00:21:30.490 align:middle line:90%
who lost the baby at one year.

00:21:30.490 --> 00:21:31.330 align:middle line:90%
So I understand.

00:21:31.330 --> 00:21:32.800 align:middle line:84%
I'm not saying
this casually or--

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:34.660 align:middle line:84%
and I'm not trying
to be cavalier.

00:21:34.660 --> 00:21:38.620 align:middle line:84%
But it's interesting that we
have now a worldwide population

00:21:38.620 --> 00:21:41.080 align:middle line:90%
crisis.

00:21:41.080 --> 00:21:43.310 align:middle line:84%
We're all freaking
out about this

00:21:43.310 --> 00:21:46.400 align:middle line:84%
because we know the
population grows exponentially

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:49.670 align:middle line:84%
and there's not enough
resources for all the people.

00:21:49.670 --> 00:21:52.610 align:middle line:84%
And the reason-- one big
reason this is happening

00:21:52.610 --> 00:21:56.040 align:middle line:84%
is because almost all our
kids make it to adulthood.

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:58.520 align:middle line:90%
So this has created a crisis.

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:02.060 align:middle line:84%
The other thing is that when
you look at which individuals

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:05.128 align:middle line:84%
in a population of, let's say,
wild animals get weeded out

00:22:05.128 --> 00:22:06.420 align:middle line:90%
and don't make it to adulthood.

00:22:06.420 --> 00:22:08.570 align:middle line:84%
This is a natural
selection system

00:22:08.570 --> 00:22:11.495 align:middle line:84%
that ensures strengthen
the genetic population.

00:22:11.495 --> 00:22:14.120 align:middle line:84%
And it will reduce many of those
problems we were talking about

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:17.510 align:middle line:84%
before, where genetic artifacts
that would be weeded out

00:22:17.510 --> 00:22:19.700 align:middle line:84%
by natural selection
by death, essentially

00:22:19.700 --> 00:22:21.920 align:middle line:84%
make it into the population
and, therefore, weaken

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:23.420 align:middle line:90%
the population at large.

00:22:23.420 --> 00:22:26.070 align:middle line:84%
This is delicate
stuff to talk about.

00:22:26.070 --> 00:22:29.450 align:middle line:84%
But I think-- it's not delicate
to talk about with any animal.

00:22:29.450 --> 00:22:31.410 align:middle line:84%
It's just delicate
talk about people.

00:22:31.410 --> 00:22:34.760 align:middle line:84%
So if we were going to
put on our biologist hat

00:22:34.760 --> 00:22:38.210 align:middle line:84%
and we were going to speak
about humans biologically,

00:22:38.210 --> 00:22:40.880 align:middle line:84%
we'd be like, oh, yeah,
this is probably not good

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:45.500 align:middle line:84%
that so many individuals, many
whom are really sick, or really

00:22:45.500 --> 00:22:47.510 align:middle line:84%
weak, or having a
failure to thrive,

00:22:47.510 --> 00:22:49.820 align:middle line:84%
go on to be reproductive
adults later.

00:22:49.820 --> 00:22:51.450 align:middle line:84%
That was not a
problem there, so it

00:22:51.450 --> 00:22:54.950 align:middle line:84%
kept hunter-gatherer
populations very strong.

00:22:54.950 --> 00:22:58.620 align:middle line:84%
We are incredibly insulated
from death in our culture

00:22:58.620 --> 00:23:01.760 align:middle line:84%
so we're not used to dealing
with anything like that.

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:04.670 align:middle line:84%
It's like taboo
even to see death.

00:23:04.670 --> 00:23:07.860 align:middle line:84%
Whereas indigenous folks
would have been like,

00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:09.050 align:middle line:90%
yep, lost that one--

00:23:09.050 --> 00:23:11.270 align:middle line:84%
not like there's no grief,
but it was more normal.

00:23:11.270 --> 00:23:13.820 align:middle line:84%
It was it was a
normal occurrence.

00:23:13.820 --> 00:23:18.410 align:middle line:84%
Even infanticide after
a child is born--

00:23:18.410 --> 00:23:20.240 align:middle line:84%
if let's say a
woman's had a child

00:23:20.240 --> 00:23:23.090 align:middle line:84%
and her husband is killed, let's
say, in a hunting accident,

00:23:23.090 --> 00:23:24.830 align:middle line:84%
it was not unheard
of to let that baby

00:23:24.830 --> 00:23:26.420 align:middle line:84%
die because you know
that you did not

00:23:26.420 --> 00:23:29.890 align:middle line:84%
have the resources
to raise that child.

00:23:29.890 --> 00:23:31.850 align:middle line:84%
Now, all our kids
make it more than

00:23:31.850 --> 00:23:36.050 align:middle line:84%
can be parented by the
parents biologically.

00:23:36.050 --> 00:23:38.242 align:middle line:84%
We have so many kids
and our population

00:23:38.242 --> 00:23:39.450 align:middle line:90%
is growing, growing, growing.

00:23:39.450 --> 00:23:41.033 align:middle line:84%
So these two things
that domestication

00:23:41.033 --> 00:23:45.670 align:middle line:84%
has given us has made
life a little easier

00:23:45.670 --> 00:23:47.540 align:middle line:90%
emotionally in some regards.

00:23:47.540 --> 00:23:49.110 align:middle line:90%
But it's certainly created--

00:23:49.110 --> 00:23:51.370 align:middle line:84%
it's a Pandora's box
and we've opened it

00:23:51.370 --> 00:23:53.732 align:middle line:84%
and there's problems
that come with that.

00:23:53.732 --> 00:23:55.240 align:middle line:90%
>> And we can't undo it now.

00:23:55.240 --> 00:23:57.530 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we're on
this path, right?

00:23:57.530 --> 00:23:58.330 align:middle line:90%
I know, right?

00:23:58.330 --> 00:23:58.600 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:58.600 --> 00:24:00.100 align:middle line:84%
And it's interesting
you bring because I

00:24:00.100 --> 00:24:02.480 align:middle line:84%
look at some really indigenous
cultures around the world.

00:24:02.480 --> 00:24:05.950 align:middle line:84%
And these things you
mention are normal for them

00:24:05.950 --> 00:24:10.300 align:middle line:84%
to consider population
control with resources.

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:12.160 align:middle line:84%
How they manage
the environment is

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:14.650 align:middle line:84%
totally different than how
we look at the environment,

00:24:14.650 --> 00:24:18.110 align:middle line:84%
because they consider
themselves of the environment.

00:24:18.110 --> 00:24:19.600 align:middle line:90%
So they are nature.

00:24:19.600 --> 00:24:23.380 align:middle line:84%
So they live in nature
and they commune with it.

00:24:23.380 --> 00:24:26.110 align:middle line:84%
Whereas, we have somewhat
sort of separated ourselves

00:24:26.110 --> 00:24:27.430 align:middle line:90%
from nature.

00:24:27.430 --> 00:24:31.160 align:middle line:84%
We cut it up, divided a gene
splice that and sort of like--

00:24:31.160 --> 00:24:32.410 align:middle line:90%
>> We're just getting started.

00:24:32.410 --> 00:24:33.510 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, right.

00:24:33.510 --> 00:24:34.843 align:middle line:90%
>> We're just getting under way.

00:24:34.843 --> 00:24:36.640 align:middle line:90%
And you know this as well.

00:24:36.640 --> 00:24:40.720 align:middle line:84%
It's like there's the
number of indigenous peoples

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:43.030 align:middle line:84%
that were in the world and
are in the world, the number

00:24:43.030 --> 00:24:44.620 align:middle line:84%
of languages and
language groups.

00:24:44.620 --> 00:24:46.600 align:middle line:90%
And you can't say--

00:24:46.600 --> 00:24:49.120 align:middle line:84%
it's tempting to say, and
I say it all the time,

00:24:49.120 --> 00:24:50.577 align:middle line:90%
well, the indigenous people.

00:24:50.577 --> 00:24:52.660 align:middle line:84%
It's like which ones and
who are we talking about?

00:24:52.660 --> 00:24:54.220 align:middle line:84%
But there are certain
things that we

00:24:54.220 --> 00:24:59.620 align:middle line:84%
can see that are sort of
trans cultural and ubiquitous.

00:24:59.620 --> 00:25:02.110 align:middle line:84%
There's this sort of way of
seeing the environment you

00:25:02.110 --> 00:25:05.110 align:middle line:84%
were just alluding to,
which is like, well, there's

00:25:05.110 --> 00:25:06.460 align:middle line:90%
human people.

00:25:06.460 --> 00:25:09.143 align:middle line:84%
But then there's like
the deer people, right?

00:25:09.143 --> 00:25:10.560 align:middle line:84%
Or the giraffe,
people or whatever

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:13.000 align:middle line:84%
is like this personage
to living creatures.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:15.520 align:middle line:90%
It's not humans.

00:25:15.520 --> 00:25:18.850 align:middle line:84%
And then everything else is like
a thing that you can just take,

00:25:18.850 --> 00:25:21.860 align:middle line:84%
like everything's just a blank
noun that you can just take,

00:25:21.860 --> 00:25:22.660 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:25:22.660 --> 00:25:25.720 align:middle line:84%
Instead, it's this understanding
that we're a type of animal,

00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:29.553 align:middle line:84%
or it might be more fair to save
with a lot of natural peoples

00:25:29.553 --> 00:25:31.720 align:middle line:84%
that it'd be like more we're
like a spiritual entity

00:25:31.720 --> 00:25:32.410 align:middle line:90%
on this--

00:25:32.410 --> 00:25:33.200 align:middle line:90%
in this place.

00:25:33.200 --> 00:25:34.450 align:middle line:90%
And so are these other beings.

00:25:34.450 --> 00:25:37.150 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, there's
a built-in respect

00:25:37.150 --> 00:25:41.560 align:middle line:84%
that our monotheistic
religions didn't necessarily

00:25:41.560 --> 00:25:43.540 align:middle line:90%
instill into us culturally.

00:25:43.540 --> 00:25:46.120 align:middle line:84%
And that might not have
been a problem initially

00:25:46.120 --> 00:25:47.920 align:middle line:84%
when we were small
enough, but now that we

00:25:47.920 --> 00:25:50.830 align:middle line:84%
have scaled out and
covered the globe,

00:25:50.830 --> 00:25:52.570 align:middle line:84%
now it's a real
problem if we interact

00:25:52.570 --> 00:25:53.980 align:middle line:90%
with the environment like that.

00:25:53.980 --> 00:25:56.800 align:middle line:84%
If we continue to interact with
the environment like everything

00:25:56.800 --> 00:26:01.090 align:middle line:84%
here is a spiritless
resource, or a resource

00:26:01.090 --> 00:26:04.090 align:middle line:84%
that doesn't require
respect, or if it's only

00:26:04.090 --> 00:26:05.703 align:middle line:90%
seen in an economic way.

00:26:05.703 --> 00:26:07.870 align:middle line:84%
And that's what-- we're
starting to see that change,

00:26:07.870 --> 00:26:10.120 align:middle line:84%
and it's good, but
it's not enough.

00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:12.405 align:middle line:84%
It won't-- I don't
think it will keep pace.

00:26:12.405 --> 00:26:13.780 align:middle line:84%
It would be like,
well, we're not

00:26:13.780 --> 00:26:16.360 align:middle line:84%
going to see trees as
like living creatures,

00:26:16.360 --> 00:26:18.550 align:middle line:90%
even though they are, right?

00:26:18.550 --> 00:26:24.182 align:middle line:84%
Or beings, even though
technically they are beings.

00:26:24.182 --> 00:26:26.140 align:middle line:84%
Instead, we'll see them
as an economic resource

00:26:26.140 --> 00:26:27.460 align:middle line:84%
and we'll think about
it like a bank account.

00:26:27.460 --> 00:26:30.370 align:middle line:84%
Like let's not spend more trees
than we're growing so that we

00:26:30.370 --> 00:26:31.660 align:middle line:90%
never hit negative, right?

00:26:31.660 --> 00:26:33.250 align:middle line:84%
We don't ever want
to go into the red.

00:26:33.250 --> 00:26:35.890 align:middle line:84%
That's-- that will lead to
more trees at some level.

00:26:35.890 --> 00:26:37.780 align:middle line:84%
But it's-- I don't
think it's enough.

00:26:37.780 --> 00:26:40.480 align:middle line:84%
And it's certainly
not enough in here

00:26:40.480 --> 00:26:43.630 align:middle line:84%
where we truly
feel an emptiness.

00:26:43.630 --> 00:26:46.360 align:middle line:90%
Because we're lonesome.

00:26:46.360 --> 00:26:48.490 align:middle line:84%
Remember, lonesome,
it's like, thank

00:26:48.490 --> 00:26:50.630 align:middle line:84%
goodness we have a
best friend, dogs.

00:26:50.630 --> 00:26:52.510 align:middle line:90%
Another domesticated animal.

00:26:52.510 --> 00:26:55.210 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, right, like us
and our dogs and our cats,

00:26:55.210 --> 00:26:57.070 align:middle line:84%
we're pretty lonely in
the world because we

00:26:57.070 --> 00:27:01.510 align:middle line:84%
have created a relationship
of emotional isolation

00:27:01.510 --> 00:27:04.330 align:middle line:90%
from our environment.

00:27:04.330 --> 00:27:07.540 align:middle line:84%
You can think of it like
this if we were to say,

00:27:07.540 --> 00:27:11.170 align:middle line:84%
let's say we were going to go
to a trekking party, like let's

00:27:11.170 --> 00:27:14.960 align:middle line:84%
say some westerners
from the UK, Europe,

00:27:14.960 --> 00:27:19.690 align:middle line:84%
and the states are going
trekking in the Himalaya.

00:27:19.690 --> 00:27:22.940 align:middle line:84%
And then we'd grab like some
indigenous folks who are

00:27:22.940 --> 00:27:24.190 align:middle line:90%
living a traditional life way.

00:27:24.190 --> 00:27:25.607 align:middle line:84%
So I'm talking
about some of these

00:27:25.607 --> 00:27:27.040 align:middle line:90%
like more uncontacted tribes.

00:27:27.040 --> 00:27:29.440 align:middle line:84%
And we look at the
two side by side.

00:27:29.440 --> 00:27:32.380 align:middle line:84%
For sure, the trekkers look
like-- almost like astronauts

00:27:32.380 --> 00:27:34.840 align:middle line:84%
compared to the
indigenous people who

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:36.730 align:middle line:84%
look much more like
a type of animal

00:27:36.730 --> 00:27:39.700 align:middle line:84%
on the landscape, a
tool using animal.

00:27:39.700 --> 00:27:41.170 align:middle line:90%
So unique, right?

00:27:41.170 --> 00:27:44.590 align:middle line:84%
One that has the ability
with both brain and digits

00:27:44.590 --> 00:27:45.940 align:middle line:90%
to manipulate the environment.

00:27:45.940 --> 00:27:47.880 align:middle line:84%
So certainly, we're
a special animal.

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:49.400 align:middle line:90%
We're unique.

00:27:49.400 --> 00:27:51.220 align:middle line:84%
But they look like
part of the landscape.

00:27:51.220 --> 00:27:55.030 align:middle line:84%
We are enclosed in
tech fabrics, boots

00:27:55.030 --> 00:27:57.640 align:middle line:84%
that insulate us from the
ground, packs full of stuff.

00:27:57.640 --> 00:28:01.450 align:middle line:84%
You put an astronaut like
from the Apollo moon landing

00:28:01.450 --> 00:28:04.690 align:middle line:84%
here and put the tracker here
and the indigenous person here,

00:28:04.690 --> 00:28:06.213 align:middle line:84%
who does the trekker
look more like?

00:28:06.213 --> 00:28:07.630 align:middle line:84%
They look more
like the astronaut.

00:28:07.630 --> 00:28:10.000 align:middle line:84%
The amount of equipment
necessary for us to just go

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:12.700 align:middle line:84%
into the environment
is a testament

00:28:12.700 --> 00:28:15.130 align:middle line:84%
to how domesticated
we've become and how

00:28:15.130 --> 00:28:18.100 align:middle line:84%
isolated we are that we need
to carry life support with us,

00:28:18.100 --> 00:28:20.680 align:middle line:84%
like as if we're going
to the moon or to Mars

00:28:20.680 --> 00:28:22.450 align:middle line:84%
but we're actually
on our own planet.

00:28:22.450 --> 00:28:24.730 align:middle line:84%
But we don't know how to
use the resources that

00:28:24.730 --> 00:28:27.880 align:middle line:84%
are available to us, so we
have to bring them all in.

00:28:27.880 --> 00:28:29.890 align:middle line:84%
And it gets complicated
because now we

00:28:29.890 --> 00:28:32.380 align:middle line:84%
have in the west here
this idea of a leave

00:28:32.380 --> 00:28:34.838 align:middle line:84%
no trace ethic in
going into nature.

00:28:34.838 --> 00:28:36.380 align:middle line:84%
So that was something
I grew up with,

00:28:36.380 --> 00:28:38.780 align:middle line:84%
which is like, if
you're going to go into,

00:28:38.780 --> 00:28:41.307 align:middle line:84%
let's say the National Forest
here where you guys just

00:28:41.307 --> 00:28:43.390 align:middle line:84%
came from, if we're going
to go into that National

00:28:43.390 --> 00:28:46.450 align:middle line:84%
Forest, the idea is, don't
start a fire with wood.

00:28:46.450 --> 00:28:48.550 align:middle line:90%
Bring your camp stove.

00:28:48.550 --> 00:28:50.680 align:middle line:84%
And that seems good because
you'll see less damage

00:28:50.680 --> 00:28:52.240 align:middle line:90%
to the landscape initially.

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:54.890 align:middle line:84%
But it also means that somewhere
they have to mine the propane,

00:28:54.890 --> 00:28:56.380 align:middle line:84%
and then somewhere they
have to bottle the propane

00:28:56.380 --> 00:28:57.730 align:middle line:90%
into these aluminum containers.

00:28:57.730 --> 00:29:00.070 align:middle line:84%
And somebody has to manufacture
the stove in a factory,

00:29:00.070 --> 00:29:02.860 align:middle line:84%
and all this pollution that
comes out of that just so I

00:29:02.860 --> 00:29:04.750 align:middle line:84%
cannot damage the
nature that I go into.

00:29:04.750 --> 00:29:07.108 align:middle line:84%
It's like, well, you
can damage that nature.

00:29:07.108 --> 00:29:08.650 align:middle line:84%
But let's leave this
nature pristine.

00:29:08.650 --> 00:29:13.510 align:middle line:84%
And we have this very, it's
sort of like, you'll see--

00:29:13.510 --> 00:29:15.820 align:middle line:84%
I've heard it said,
and I can't speak

00:29:15.820 --> 00:29:18.188 align:middle line:84%
on behalf of First
Nations People

00:29:18.188 --> 00:29:20.230 align:middle line:84%
or Native American people
here on this continent.

00:29:20.230 --> 00:29:21.030 align:middle line:90%
I won't try to.

00:29:21.030 --> 00:29:24.310 align:middle line:84%
But I have heard a sentiment
echoed several times.

00:29:24.310 --> 00:29:30.608 align:middle line:84%
When people from our culture
see the reservations,

00:29:30.608 --> 00:29:32.650 align:middle line:84%
and they'll see what looks
like a lot of garbage,

00:29:32.650 --> 00:29:35.200 align:middle line:84%
and sometimes it'll be like
cars rusting out over here,

00:29:35.200 --> 00:29:37.940 align:middle line:84%
plastic strewn about in people's
yards and stuff, and be like,

00:29:37.940 --> 00:29:40.540 align:middle line:84%
and why do they not
just clean that up?

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:42.130 align:middle line:90%
And for them, what--

00:29:42.130 --> 00:29:43.930 align:middle line:84%
again, I've heard
this said and echoed

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:45.910 align:middle line:84%
several times it's
like, you guys just

00:29:45.910 --> 00:29:50.170 align:middle line:84%
think that if you go bury
it over there, it goes away.

00:29:50.170 --> 00:29:52.000 align:middle line:84%
And we don't think
like that, right?

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.850 align:middle line:84%
So we have this idea that,
well, we have designated

00:29:54.850 --> 00:29:56.130 align:middle line:90%
this for destruction.

00:29:56.130 --> 00:29:57.940 align:middle line:84%
We'll put all this
stuff there so we can

00:29:57.940 --> 00:30:00.280 align:middle line:90%
keep this looking really clean.

00:30:00.280 --> 00:30:01.540 align:middle line:90%
It's like a shell game.

00:30:01.540 --> 00:30:04.100 align:middle line:84%
We just keep moving stuff
around, forgetting that, hey,

00:30:04.100 --> 00:30:07.030 align:middle line:84%
the environment's one
contiguous interconnected thing.

00:30:07.030 --> 00:30:10.120 align:middle line:84%
And this is a testament to
how we relate to it, right?

00:30:10.120 --> 00:30:12.790 align:middle line:84%
It's like, well, I want to
keep my face really pretty,

00:30:12.790 --> 00:30:15.760 align:middle line:84%
but I'm going to scratch up and
cut up my legs or something.

00:30:15.760 --> 00:30:17.890 align:middle line:84%
It's like that's--
it's all one body.

00:30:17.890 --> 00:30:21.100 align:middle line:84%
And we live on that body and
we're interacting with it.

00:30:21.100 --> 00:30:22.870 align:middle line:84%
Like we came from
another planet.

00:30:22.870 --> 00:30:24.280 align:middle line:90%
And we're not from here.

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:28.865 align:middle line:84%
And we don't have
anywhere else to go.

00:30:28.865 --> 00:30:30.990 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I think that's
important for people to get.

00:30:30.990 --> 00:30:34.625 align:middle line:84%
This idea of like a lunar
base or a trip to Mars,

00:30:34.625 --> 00:30:36.000 align:middle line:84%
we're not talking
about something

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:37.090 align:middle line:90%
that's going on next week.

00:30:37.090 --> 00:30:38.910 align:middle line:90%
We have no backup plan here.

00:30:38.910 --> 00:30:39.840 align:middle line:90%
This is the home.

00:30:39.840 --> 00:30:41.630 align:middle line:84%
This is the placenta,
or whatever.

00:30:41.630 --> 00:30:45.250 align:middle line:84%
This is the womb, like we--
this Earth is what we have.

00:30:45.250 --> 00:30:48.710 align:middle line:84%
We don't even know if we
could survive out there.

00:30:48.710 --> 00:30:52.330 align:middle line:84%
It's extremely unrealistic that
that's how our future goes,

00:30:52.330 --> 00:30:53.130 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:30:53.130 --> 00:30:57.210 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the rise and fall
of civilizations through time,

00:30:57.210 --> 00:30:59.800 align:middle line:90%
it's very unrealistic.

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:01.650 align:middle line:90%
The probability is low.

00:31:01.650 --> 00:31:04.773 align:middle line:84%
We need to bank on
protecting this place,

00:31:04.773 --> 00:31:07.065 align:middle line:84%
not running somewhere else
and then destroying that one

00:31:07.065 --> 00:31:08.790 align:middle line:90%
and going to the next one.

00:31:08.790 --> 00:31:10.320 align:middle line:84%
If we're going to
do that, we need

00:31:10.320 --> 00:31:11.737 align:middle line:84%
to have a different
ethic with how

00:31:11.737 --> 00:31:13.590 align:middle line:90%
we interact with the landscape.

00:31:13.590 --> 00:31:17.490 align:middle line:84%
And it's not going to come
from just recycling and trying

00:31:17.490 --> 00:31:19.630 align:middle line:84%
to do leave no trace
in the environment.

00:31:19.630 --> 00:31:21.390 align:middle line:84%
It's got to come
from people having

00:31:21.390 --> 00:31:25.110 align:middle line:84%
meaningful interactions with
the landscape that can't

00:31:25.110 --> 00:31:27.653 align:middle line:90%
be replaced by something else.

00:31:27.653 --> 00:31:29.070 align:middle line:84%
You could look at
what I do, which

00:31:29.070 --> 00:31:31.740 align:middle line:90%
is hunt, fish, and forage food.

00:31:31.740 --> 00:31:34.210 align:middle line:84%
And you can think like it's a
hobby, because I don't really

00:31:34.210 --> 00:31:35.010 align:middle line:90%
need to.

00:31:35.010 --> 00:31:36.720 align:middle line:84%
I can go right down
to the supermarket.

00:31:36.720 --> 00:31:37.690 align:middle line:90%
I have the resources.

00:31:37.690 --> 00:31:38.490 align:middle line:90%
I have a vehicle.

00:31:38.490 --> 00:31:42.210 align:middle line:84%
I have the money to go
buy all my food if I want.

00:31:42.210 --> 00:31:45.400 align:middle line:84%
But I choose to hunt,
fish and forage.

00:31:45.400 --> 00:31:47.860 align:middle line:84%
It looks to some people
like it's my hobby.

00:31:47.860 --> 00:31:51.220 align:middle line:84%
Like, oh, it's just
golf, or Frisbee,

00:31:51.220 --> 00:31:52.840 align:middle line:90%
or whatever other hobby.

00:31:52.840 --> 00:31:54.910 align:middle line:84%
And for me it's like,
no, it's not that.

00:31:54.910 --> 00:31:56.560 align:middle line:90%
It's not a sport.

00:31:56.560 --> 00:32:00.287 align:middle line:84%
It's probably the best way
to say it's like a practice.

00:32:00.287 --> 00:32:02.620 align:middle line:84%
Most people who meditate don't
think of their meditation

00:32:02.620 --> 00:32:04.180 align:middle line:90%
as a sport, right?

00:32:04.180 --> 00:32:06.560 align:middle line:84%
They don't think of their
yoga, usually, as a sport.

00:32:06.560 --> 00:32:08.110 align:middle line:90%
It's a practice, right?

00:32:08.110 --> 00:32:10.370 align:middle line:84%
It takes discipline
to show up and do it.

00:32:10.370 --> 00:32:12.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, harvesting and
processing your own food

00:32:12.850 --> 00:32:15.070 align:middle line:90%
takes quite a lot of discipline.

00:32:15.070 --> 00:32:16.580 align:middle line:90%
It provides subsistence.

00:32:16.580 --> 00:32:19.320 align:middle line:90%
It provides calories for me.

00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:22.740 align:middle line:84%
But I spend probably
sometimes more resources

00:32:22.740 --> 00:32:24.680 align:middle line:90%
doing it than I actually get.

00:32:24.680 --> 00:32:26.940 align:middle line:84%
So it's not really subsistence,
and it's not really

00:32:26.940 --> 00:32:28.510 align:middle line:90%
a sport or a hobby.

00:32:28.510 --> 00:32:32.730 align:middle line:84%
It's a practice that alters
how I interact with landscapes.

00:32:32.730 --> 00:32:34.350 align:middle line:84%
Now when I move
through landscapes,

00:32:34.350 --> 00:32:36.620 align:middle line:90%
these are like a kitchen to me.

00:32:36.620 --> 00:32:38.310 align:middle line:90%
It's like an extension of me.

00:32:38.310 --> 00:32:40.590 align:middle line:90%
It's part of my home.

00:32:40.590 --> 00:32:44.300 align:middle line:84%
If Walmart wants to put
a store into a landscape

00:32:44.300 --> 00:32:49.010 align:middle line:84%
where I harvest food, who's the
first person out there to say,

00:32:49.010 --> 00:32:52.000 align:middle line:84%
hey, no, this place needs
to remain an open space.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:54.730 align:middle line:84%
Not the environmentalist
back in the city

00:32:54.730 --> 00:32:57.670 align:middle line:84%
who's just actually
using all those resources

00:32:57.670 --> 00:33:01.210 align:middle line:84%
and probably going to
shop at that Walmart.

00:33:01.210 --> 00:33:06.170 align:middle line:84%
They-- for sure, they believe
in caring for the environment.

00:33:06.170 --> 00:33:08.680 align:middle line:84%
But at such a level
of removal that they

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:11.715 align:middle line:84%
can fall into these ideas of
like carbon offset credits,

00:33:11.715 --> 00:33:13.840 align:middle line:84%
right, where it's like,
oh, yeah, that makes sense,

00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:16.720 align:middle line:84%
OK, we'll destroy that but
we'll fix something over here

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:19.610 align:middle line:84%
Whereas I'm like, no, you can't
destroy, that is important.

00:33:19.610 --> 00:33:20.410 align:middle line:90%
I fish there.

00:33:20.410 --> 00:33:22.270 align:middle line:84%
I hunt there I.
Get my food there.

00:33:22.270 --> 00:33:24.370 align:middle line:84%
So I'm a stakeholder in
caring for that landscape.

00:33:24.370 --> 00:33:25.870 align:middle line:84%
And what I've noticed
is when people

00:33:25.870 --> 00:33:29.620 align:middle line:84%
have these meaningful,
extractive, sustainably

00:33:29.620 --> 00:33:31.712 align:middle line:84%
extractive relationships,
they care about a place.

00:33:31.712 --> 00:33:33.670 align:middle line:84%
And that's what-- where
one of the things about

00:33:33.670 --> 00:33:36.092 align:middle line:84%
indigenous people
when you see what

00:33:36.092 --> 00:33:38.050 align:middle line:84%
happens when they would
be moved, for instance,

00:33:38.050 --> 00:33:39.820 align:middle line:90%
the punishment to the Apache.

00:33:39.820 --> 00:33:43.810 align:middle line:84%
Like the Apache were the
last people fighting the US

00:33:43.810 --> 00:33:45.610 align:middle line:90%
government, right?

00:33:45.610 --> 00:33:48.040 align:middle line:84%
And they were moved
eventually, Geronimo

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:52.120 align:middle line:84%
and the rest of these people
were moved from Arizona

00:33:52.120 --> 00:33:53.500 align:middle line:90%
to Florida.

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:55.090 align:middle line:84%
So we're talking
about people who

00:33:55.090 --> 00:33:57.970 align:middle line:84%
are adapted for
countless generations

00:33:57.970 --> 00:33:59.790 align:middle line:84%
to living on this
arid landscape.

00:33:59.790 --> 00:34:01.290 align:middle line:84%
They know the plants
that are there.

00:34:01.290 --> 00:34:02.440 align:middle line:84%
They know the animals
that are there.

00:34:02.440 --> 00:34:03.857 align:middle line:84%
They understand
the seasons there.

00:34:03.857 --> 00:34:05.660 align:middle line:90%
They are of that place.

00:34:05.660 --> 00:34:08.860 align:middle line:84%
They're literally
shaped by that place.

00:34:08.860 --> 00:34:11.500 align:middle line:84%
And then you stick them in
the wettest, most humid place.

00:34:11.500 --> 00:34:13.449 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's a
punishment, right?

00:34:13.449 --> 00:34:15.429 align:middle line:84%
When you move
peoples around, they

00:34:15.429 --> 00:34:18.040 align:middle line:84%
care-- they are no
longer adapted to place.

00:34:18.040 --> 00:34:19.335 align:middle line:90%
And now they suffer.

00:34:19.335 --> 00:34:21.460 align:middle line:84%
Most of the reservations
here in the United States,

00:34:21.460 --> 00:34:23.889 align:middle line:84%
they're not-- it's not as if
they were, oh, well, choose

00:34:23.889 --> 00:34:25.750 align:middle line:84%
your prime piece of land
where you get your stuff

00:34:25.750 --> 00:34:27.460 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll cordon
that off and you've

00:34:27.460 --> 00:34:28.570 align:middle line:90%
got to just hang out there.

00:34:28.570 --> 00:34:30.195 align:middle line:84%
It's like, hey, we're
going to send you

00:34:30.195 --> 00:34:32.050 align:middle line:84%
the badlands, the place
where you guys knew

00:34:32.050 --> 00:34:35.350 align:middle line:84%
there was no food, and you
knew there was no resources

00:34:35.350 --> 00:34:36.370 align:middle line:90%
to start farming that.

00:34:36.370 --> 00:34:40.270 align:middle line:84%
It's like that's-- and for
me, if you stick me in another

00:34:40.270 --> 00:34:41.947 align:middle line:84%
place, I don't know
the plants there.

00:34:41.947 --> 00:34:43.239 align:middle line:90%
I don't know the animals there.

00:34:43.239 --> 00:34:45.850 align:middle line:84%
I've spent a lot of time,
invested a lot of energy

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:47.590 align:middle line:90%
into learning this place.

00:34:47.590 --> 00:34:51.120 align:middle line:84%
So it's not that a landscape
is not replaceable to me.

00:34:51.120 --> 00:34:54.242 align:middle line:84%
And that's why you become a
staunch protector of a place

00:34:54.242 --> 00:34:56.659 align:middle line:84%
once you have a meaningful
interaction with the landscape.

00:34:56.659 --> 00:35:00.880 align:middle line:84%
And when I say meaningful, I
mean like my cells in my body

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:04.450 align:middle line:84%
contain carbon that come from
