00:37:34.410 --> 00:37:37.830 align:middle line:84%
They create the wetlands that
bring in migratory birds.

00:37:37.830 --> 00:37:41.230 align:middle line:84%
They create ponds that
backfill and trout move in.

00:37:41.230 --> 00:37:44.910 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's just amazing
how they create more habitat.

00:37:44.910 --> 00:37:46.470 align:middle line:90%
People do this, too.

00:37:46.470 --> 00:37:48.120 align:middle line:84%
We are a type of
animal that engineers

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:50.740 align:middle line:84%
landscapes in such a way even
as indigenous people, right?

00:37:50.740 --> 00:37:54.090 align:middle line:84%
Remember, pre-agricultural,
pre-industrial indigenous

00:37:54.090 --> 00:37:59.610 align:middle line:84%
peoples were burning landscapes
with fire to create open space.

00:37:59.610 --> 00:38:02.500 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes just to get away
from biting insects, right?

00:38:02.500 --> 00:38:04.140 align:middle line:84%
It's like you get
into the woods,

00:38:04.140 --> 00:38:05.010 align:middle line:90%
mosquitoes are all over you.

00:38:05.010 --> 00:38:06.885 align:middle line:84%
You get out in a field
where there's a breeze

00:38:06.885 --> 00:38:08.590 align:middle line:84%
and suddenly you get
a break from that.

00:38:08.590 --> 00:38:11.100 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes you burn a landscape
to bring up new growth.

00:38:11.100 --> 00:38:12.808 align:middle line:84%
For instance, when I
foraged blueberries,

00:38:12.808 --> 00:38:14.400 align:middle line:84%
sometimes they'll
burn the plains.

00:38:14.400 --> 00:38:15.775 align:middle line:84%
And the next year
the blueberries

00:38:15.775 --> 00:38:17.040 align:middle line:90%
are so much more prolific.

00:38:17.040 --> 00:38:19.770 align:middle line:84%
Or the morel mushrooms,
or whatever it is.

00:38:19.770 --> 00:38:22.080 align:middle line:84%
So they're cutting trees
down for resources.

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:25.200 align:middle line:84%
They're-- think about a lot
of times people imagine that

00:38:25.200 --> 00:38:29.040 align:middle line:84%
for hunter gatherers that they
would have to move because they

00:38:29.040 --> 00:38:30.847 align:middle line:90%
depleted the food resources.

00:38:30.847 --> 00:38:33.180 align:middle line:84%
But when you actually go out
and play with some of this,

00:38:33.180 --> 00:38:37.320 align:middle line:84%
you realize, well, you probably
are actually reducing your fuel

00:38:37.320 --> 00:38:38.640 align:middle line:90%
before your food.

00:38:38.640 --> 00:38:40.900 align:middle line:84%
In other words, you're
running out of stuff to burn.

00:38:40.900 --> 00:38:43.920 align:middle line:90%
Especially prior to metal tools.

00:38:43.920 --> 00:38:48.120 align:middle line:84%
When Europeans came to North
America, it was essentially,

00:38:48.120 --> 00:38:49.590 align:middle line:84%
we could say, the
Stone Age here.

00:38:49.590 --> 00:38:51.780 align:middle line:90%
They did not have metal tools.

00:38:51.780 --> 00:38:53.310 align:middle line:84%
Imagine you are
cutting a tree down

00:38:53.310 --> 00:38:56.760 align:middle line:84%
with an adds that's
a stone head, right?

00:38:56.760 --> 00:38:58.060 align:middle line:90%
You have to make that.

00:38:58.060 --> 00:39:00.060 align:middle line:84%
And then we're not talking
about a cutting blade

00:39:00.060 --> 00:39:02.790 align:middle line:90%
that you just easily resharpen.

00:39:02.790 --> 00:39:04.650 align:middle line:84%
You're more likely
to want to burn

00:39:04.650 --> 00:39:05.820 align:middle line:90%
wood that's already fallen.

00:39:05.820 --> 00:39:08.520 align:middle line:90%
Wood that's washed up on shore.

00:39:08.520 --> 00:39:10.860 align:middle line:84%
Wood that can be snapped
off, lower limbs, things

00:39:10.860 --> 00:39:13.920 align:middle line:84%
like that that are dry on
conifers and things like that.

00:39:13.920 --> 00:39:15.610 align:middle line:84%
And eventually, you
run out of that.

00:39:15.610 --> 00:39:17.568 align:middle line:84%
But as you go through
the landscape doing that,

00:39:17.568 --> 00:39:19.020 align:middle line:84%
you start breaking
that stuff off.

00:39:19.020 --> 00:39:20.730 align:middle line:84%
You're opening up
all this space.

00:39:20.730 --> 00:39:21.840 align:middle line:90%
Air moves in there.

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:23.670 align:middle line:84%
Animals can now
move through there.

00:39:23.670 --> 00:39:26.190 align:middle line:84%
You cut stuff down and
young shoots come up.

00:39:26.190 --> 00:39:28.890 align:middle line:84%
And deer moves out--
come in for that stuff.

00:39:28.890 --> 00:39:30.750 align:middle line:84%
So we actually
engineer landscapes

00:39:30.750 --> 00:39:33.420 align:middle line:84%
and then we'd move along, and
move along, and move along.

00:39:33.420 --> 00:39:36.520 align:middle line:84%
And as we did that, nature
became more productive.

00:39:36.520 --> 00:39:39.360 align:middle line:84%
There's a story I really like
out of the Christian Bible,

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:42.900 align:middle line:84%
or I guess, out of
the Torah, as well.

00:39:42.900 --> 00:39:46.920 align:middle line:84%
This idea that the first
people were put into a garden

00:39:46.920 --> 00:39:49.740 align:middle line:84%
to be the gardeners of it,
to name all the animals,

00:39:49.740 --> 00:39:51.450 align:middle line:90%
and to care for the garden.

00:39:51.450 --> 00:39:53.910 align:middle line:84%
And I think there's something
really universally true

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:57.480 align:middle line:84%
in there is that humans,
essentially what we are,

00:39:57.480 --> 00:40:01.920 align:middle line:84%
is the self-aware gardeners
of the wild world.

00:40:01.920 --> 00:40:05.490 align:middle line:84%
And it's only when we went
down this path of domestication

00:40:05.490 --> 00:40:07.650 align:middle line:90%
that we lost that.

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:11.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, we are like the
antithesis of that.

00:40:11.910 --> 00:40:14.400 align:middle line:84%
We have gone from being
gardeners to being

00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:16.980 align:middle line:84%
just like the
harvesters of it, right?

00:40:16.980 --> 00:40:18.930 align:middle line:84%
And we're eating our
way down the food chain.

00:40:18.930 --> 00:40:22.560 align:middle line:84%
This is a really scary thing,
like when Europeans first came

00:40:22.560 --> 00:40:25.290 align:middle line:90%
to North America, this was--

00:40:25.290 --> 00:40:27.245 align:middle line:84%
they couldn't
understand the richness.

00:40:27.245 --> 00:40:28.620 align:middle line:84%
They'd come from
a place that had

00:40:28.620 --> 00:40:31.380 align:middle line:90%
been depleted for 1,000 years.

00:40:31.380 --> 00:40:32.180 align:middle line:90%
They get here.

00:40:32.180 --> 00:40:36.540 align:middle line:84%
Not only are the force intact,
