00:43:54.980 --> 00:43:56.180 align:middle line:90%
about on the physical level.

00:43:56.180 --> 00:44:01.150 align:middle line:84%
On the emotional level,
almost across the--

00:44:01.150 --> 00:44:03.560 align:middle line:84%
hunter-gatherers are called
the original affluent people

00:44:03.560 --> 00:44:05.842 align:middle line:90%
by anthropologists.

00:44:05.842 --> 00:44:08.300 align:middle line:84%
Even though they don't have
financial wealth from what they

00:44:08.300 --> 00:44:12.220 align:middle line:84%
do, they live very well,
and they are much happier,

00:44:12.220 --> 00:44:15.830 align:middle line:84%
and their mental health is
so much better than ours.

00:44:15.830 --> 00:44:17.480 align:middle line:90%
So that's really important.

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:19.040 align:middle line:84%
Because if you're
like, would you

00:44:19.040 --> 00:44:22.130 align:middle line:84%
like to live 10 more
depressed years or 10

00:44:22.130 --> 00:44:24.510 align:middle line:90%
less but happy the whole time--

00:44:24.510 --> 00:44:26.450 align:middle line:84%
and not happy like they
never have hard times.

00:44:26.450 --> 00:44:28.610 align:middle line:84%
It's the resiliency,
emotional resiliency,

00:44:28.610 --> 00:44:30.290 align:middle line:90%
and the lack of mental illness.

00:44:30.290 --> 00:44:34.160 align:middle line:84%
This idea of suiciding ourselves
that we see so common now,

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:37.610 align:middle line:84%
the desperation that I think
comes from this lonesomeness

00:44:37.610 --> 00:44:41.428 align:middle line:84%
from this isolation from
one another and from nature.

00:44:41.428 --> 00:44:42.970 align:middle line:84%
Part of it too is
you brought up sort

00:44:42.970 --> 00:44:45.400 align:middle line:84%
of the businessman,
who is like, seize

00:44:45.400 --> 00:44:47.920 align:middle line:90%
the world as a zero-sum game.

00:44:47.920 --> 00:44:50.508 align:middle line:84%
So I need these resources
because if I don't take them,

00:44:50.508 --> 00:44:52.300 align:middle line:84%
someone else will take
them, and I will not

00:44:52.300 --> 00:44:55.000 align:middle line:84%
have enough resources
because it's a zero-sum game.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:57.250 align:middle line:84%
Whereas for the indigenous
peoples of the world

00:44:57.250 --> 00:45:01.360 align:middle line:84%
or the hunter-gatherers of the
world, everything is shared.

00:45:01.360 --> 00:45:04.060 align:middle line:84%
And usually, there--
because each society

00:45:04.060 --> 00:45:07.150 align:middle line:84%
is different, but usually
embedded within that society

00:45:07.150 --> 00:45:09.910 align:middle line:84%
are a system of sort
of rules and taboos

00:45:09.910 --> 00:45:11.982 align:middle line:84%
that make sure that
everyone is taken care of.

00:45:11.982 --> 00:45:14.440 align:middle line:84%
That doesn't mean that some
people don't have higher status

00:45:14.440 --> 00:45:17.380 align:middle line:84%
or that some people are
going to be better hunters.

00:45:17.380 --> 00:45:20.050 align:middle line:84%
But here, when I go hunt,
I bring that animal home.

00:45:20.050 --> 00:45:23.650 align:middle line:84%
It's mine, and I get to decide
what I want to do with it.

00:45:23.650 --> 00:45:26.140 align:middle line:84%
Whereas if I brought
it back to a tribe,

00:45:26.140 --> 00:45:29.050 align:middle line:84%
typically it's not the
hunter who gets that.

00:45:29.050 --> 00:45:31.312 align:middle line:84%
It's distributed out
amongst the people.

00:45:31.312 --> 00:45:33.020 align:middle line:84%
And usually there's
some system for that,

00:45:33.020 --> 00:45:34.840 align:middle line:84%
whether it's a
gift-based system or it's

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:37.030 align:middle line:84%
a taboo-based
system of it's taboo

00:45:37.030 --> 00:45:39.387 align:middle line:84%
to be arrogant
about your hunting,

00:45:39.387 --> 00:45:41.470 align:middle line:84%
and therefore you don't
want to be seen as someone

00:45:41.470 --> 00:45:43.480 align:middle line:90%
who thinks this is yours.

00:45:43.480 --> 00:45:45.340 align:middle line:84%
There's always these
systems for that.

00:45:45.340 --> 00:45:47.980 align:middle line:84%
So they don't see it
as a zero-sum game,

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:49.570 align:middle line:90%
because it's not one.

00:45:49.570 --> 00:45:52.630 align:middle line:84%
There is enough to go around,
but we're not sharing.

00:45:52.630 --> 00:45:55.060 align:middle line:84%
However, there's also
an interesting thing--

00:45:55.060 --> 00:45:56.190 align:middle line:90%
I saw a study--

00:45:56.190 --> 00:45:58.700 align:middle line:84%
I believe this was
either Inuit or Inupiat,

00:45:58.700 --> 00:46:01.540 align:middle line:84%
but it's a northern
tier group in the Arctic

00:46:01.540 --> 00:46:05.450 align:middle line:84%
where they created,
essentially, a map of data

00:46:05.450 --> 00:46:07.810 align:middle line:84%
points of all these
individuals and families

00:46:07.810 --> 00:46:09.670 align:middle line:84%
and how food was
shared amongst them.

00:46:09.670 --> 00:46:12.400 align:middle line:84%
And so each point
is an individual.

00:46:12.400 --> 00:46:16.150 align:middle line:84%
And you see this incredibly
intricate, almost spider

00:46:16.150 --> 00:46:20.200 align:middle line:84%
webbing of how food is shared,
how resources are shared.

00:46:20.200 --> 00:46:22.060 align:middle line:84%
Then they do the
same thing with money

00:46:22.060 --> 00:46:23.660 align:middle line:90%
that comes into the community.

00:46:23.660 --> 00:46:26.290 align:middle line:84%
And now you have just
the couple of lines.

00:46:26.290 --> 00:46:28.390 align:middle line:84%
People don't share
money the way that they

00:46:28.390 --> 00:46:32.530 align:middle line:84%
share natural resources because
money in the economic model

00:46:32.530 --> 00:46:35.080 align:middle line:84%
is much more of a zero-sum
game, like we are talking about.

00:46:35.080 --> 00:46:37.205 align:middle line:84%
It isn't something where
it's like, oh, I got $100,

00:46:37.205 --> 00:46:39.880 align:middle line:84%
so I want to make sure
all my friends get $20.

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:43.223 align:middle line:84%
Whereas when I get a deer, I
like to share that meat out.

00:46:43.223 --> 00:46:44.890 align:middle line:84%
So I think that that's
a big part of it,

00:46:44.890 --> 00:46:47.560 align:middle line:84%
is that those of us who've been
raised in this economic model

00:46:47.560 --> 00:46:48.400 align:middle line:90%
become--

00:46:48.400 --> 00:46:50.470 align:middle line:90%
we isolate ourselves through--

00:46:50.470 --> 00:46:51.580 align:middle line:90%
I don't want to say greed.

00:46:51.580 --> 00:46:54.070 align:middle line:84%
It's actually the smart
way to handle money.

00:46:54.070 --> 00:46:55.270 align:middle line:90%
That's the thing.

00:46:55.270 --> 00:46:58.550 align:middle line:84%
You're being more adapted
to the economic environment.

00:46:58.550 --> 00:47:00.460 align:middle line:84%
So you're fit for
that environment,

00:47:00.460 --> 00:47:03.070 align:middle line:84%
but not fit for
the natural world.

00:47:03.070 --> 00:47:06.010 align:middle line:84%
To come back to what
you were talking about--

00:47:06.010 --> 00:47:08.260 align:middle line:84%
I mean, for a lot of
people, like if you've

00:47:08.260 --> 00:47:11.830 align:middle line:84%
been living in the city and your
closest experience of nature

00:47:11.830 --> 00:47:15.790 align:middle line:84%
is eating alfalfa
sprouts at the juice bar,

00:47:15.790 --> 00:47:18.850 align:middle line:84%
then it starts with actually
maybe just getting out

00:47:18.850 --> 00:47:23.050 align:middle line:84%
in the park and just
getting out into nature.

00:47:23.050 --> 00:47:25.270 align:middle line:84%
Certainly for me
it's been decades

00:47:25.270 --> 00:47:29.110 align:middle line:84%
of unwinding this
stuff, confronting a lot

00:47:29.110 --> 00:47:30.700 align:middle line:90%
of the taboos along the way.

00:47:30.700 --> 00:47:33.480 align:middle line:84%
For instance, like you brought
up, just taking your shoes off.

00:47:33.480 --> 00:47:37.330 align:middle line:84%
There's a tremendous taboo
against taking your shoes off.

00:47:37.330 --> 00:47:38.530 align:middle line:90%
It's incredible.

00:47:38.530 --> 00:47:40.540 align:middle line:84%
I mean, every store
has a sign saying

00:47:40.540 --> 00:47:42.340 align:middle line:84%
you can't come in
there if you do that.

00:47:42.340 --> 00:47:45.280 align:middle line:84%
And there's places where
it's considered normal--

00:47:45.280 --> 00:47:47.300 align:middle line:90%
in your shower, on the beach.

00:47:47.300 --> 00:47:50.050 align:middle line:84%
But if you go outside of where
it's normal without your shoes

00:47:50.050 --> 00:47:53.182 align:middle line:84%
on, people start to get
all in a bunch about it.

00:47:53.182 --> 00:47:54.890 align:middle line:84%
It's like, oh-- they're
not used to that.

00:47:54.890 --> 00:47:56.590 align:middle line:84%
Well, we have a
lot of those that

00:47:56.590 --> 00:48:01.210 align:middle line:84%
keep us from expressing
ourselves as animals.

00:48:01.210 --> 00:48:03.370 align:middle line:90%
So it's our smell.

00:48:03.370 --> 00:48:04.600 align:middle line:90%
It's our hair.

00:48:04.600 --> 00:48:07.278 align:middle line:84%
It's our clothes, and shoes,
and the way that we walk,

00:48:07.278 --> 00:48:08.320 align:middle line:90%
and the way that we talk.

00:48:08.320 --> 00:48:10.988 align:middle line:84%
We have a lot of taboo in
our culture against wildness.

00:48:10.988 --> 00:48:13.030 align:middle line:84%
And you can just see this
if you look up the word

00:48:13.030 --> 00:48:14.180 align:middle line:90%
"wild" in the dictionary.

00:48:14.180 --> 00:48:14.980 align:middle line:90%
It's incredible.

00:48:14.980 --> 00:48:17.530 align:middle line:84%
There'll be about 14
entries, depending

00:48:17.530 --> 00:48:18.900 align:middle line:90%
on the dictionary you use.

00:48:18.900 --> 00:48:21.450 align:middle line:84%
And one of them will be
about biological wildness,

00:48:21.450 --> 00:48:23.050 align:middle line:90%
a thing in its natural state.

00:48:23.050 --> 00:48:24.940 align:middle line:90%
And the rest are all negative.

00:48:24.940 --> 00:48:26.750 align:middle line:84%
That was a wild
party last night.

00:48:26.750 --> 00:48:28.140 align:middle line:90%
It got crazy.

00:48:28.140 --> 00:48:30.290 align:middle line:84%
Oh, so and so's acting
a little too wild.

00:48:30.290 --> 00:48:32.680 align:middle line:84%
Oh, that was a wild
storm last night--

00:48:32.680 --> 00:48:37.240 align:middle line:84%
always these negative
connotations to wildness.

00:48:37.240 --> 00:48:41.110 align:middle line:84%
We see wildness as a threatening
external force rather than

00:48:41.110 --> 00:48:42.700 align:middle line:90%
a thing that we're a part of.

00:48:42.700 --> 00:48:44.770 align:middle line:84%
And I think mentally
unwinding that

00:48:44.770 --> 00:48:49.850 align:middle line:84%
is a really important part of
getting back to some sanity.

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:51.410 align:middle line:84%
After that is
starting to develop

00:48:51.410 --> 00:48:54.450 align:middle line:84%
meaningful relationships
with the natural world.

00:48:54.450 --> 00:48:58.400 align:middle line:84%
And I think that comes from
getting to know species.

00:48:58.400 --> 00:49:01.130 align:middle line:90%
I'm not so big on--

00:49:01.130 --> 00:49:04.100 align:middle line:84%
for taxonomic purposes, I
have no problem breaking

00:49:04.100 --> 00:49:06.903 align:middle line:84%
the world up into animals,
and plants, and fungi,

00:49:06.903 --> 00:49:09.320 align:middle line:84%
and bacteria, and algaes, and
all these different kingdoms

00:49:09.320 --> 00:49:10.120 align:middle line:90%
of life.

00:49:10.120 --> 00:49:13.670 align:middle line:84%
But functionally, I just
think of them all as species.

00:49:13.670 --> 00:49:15.800 align:middle line:84%
I try not to think that
there's something better

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:18.200 align:middle line:90%
about an animal than a plant.

00:49:18.200 --> 00:49:19.738 align:middle line:84%
I think that's a
specieist approach.

00:49:19.738 --> 00:49:21.530 align:middle line:84%
It's one of the issues
that I would take up

00:49:21.530 --> 00:49:23.360 align:middle line:84%
with the modern
vegan movement, is

00:49:23.360 --> 00:49:28.400 align:middle line:84%
that it has a tendency to assume
that biologically an animal has

00:49:28.400 --> 00:49:30.170 align:middle line:84%
more inherent value
than a plant, which

00:49:30.170 --> 00:49:33.510 align:middle line:84%
I don't think makes sense at a
biological or spiritual level

00:49:33.510 --> 00:49:34.310 align:middle line:90%
to me.

00:49:34.310 --> 00:49:35.110 align:middle line:90%
I don't like that.

00:49:35.110 --> 00:49:38.450 align:middle line:84%
So I don't care if it's a
plant, or an animal, or fungi.

00:49:38.450 --> 00:49:41.640 align:middle line:84%
What I want is to have
relationships with the species.

00:49:41.640 --> 00:49:44.630 align:middle line:84%
So in my environment,
let's say I know--

00:49:44.630 --> 00:49:48.560 align:middle line:84%
I work with several
dozen plants, animals--

00:49:48.560 --> 00:49:51.170 align:middle line:90%
high dozens, let's say.

00:49:51.170 --> 00:49:55.430 align:middle line:84%
Each one of those is
like a friend of mine,

00:49:55.430 --> 00:49:59.860 align:middle line:84%
except that there is many
specimens of that species.

00:49:59.860 --> 00:50:02.252 align:middle line:84%
So we could take a walk
through these woods.

00:50:02.252 --> 00:50:03.710 align:middle line:84%
And let's say you're
not from here,

00:50:03.710 --> 00:50:05.418 align:middle line:84%
and you're not familiar
with what's here.

00:50:05.418 --> 00:50:08.300 align:middle line:84%
So everything is just
sort of green and brown,

00:50:08.300 --> 00:50:09.110 align:middle line:90%
going past you.

00:50:09.110 --> 00:50:11.390 align:middle line:84%
And we're talking about
something unrelated to nature

00:50:11.390 --> 00:50:11.720 align:middle line:90%
maybe.

00:50:11.720 --> 00:50:14.070 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about your
job or something like that.

00:50:14.070 --> 00:50:17.540 align:middle line:84%
And it's just the backdrop,
like as if the natural world is

00:50:17.540 --> 00:50:20.810 align:middle line:84%
the stage upon which we
act out the human drama

00:50:20.810 --> 00:50:22.438 align:middle line:90%
versus the place where we live.

00:50:22.438 --> 00:50:24.980 align:middle line:84%
This happens to me all the time,
because I'll take people out

00:50:24.980 --> 00:50:28.640 align:middle line:84%
with me and I'll observe them
seeing just nothing really,

00:50:28.640 --> 00:50:30.110 align:middle line:90%
just it's a blur of green.

00:50:30.110 --> 00:50:33.390 align:middle line:84%
And I'm seeing
individuals in that blur.

00:50:33.390 --> 00:50:34.280 align:middle line:90%
That's a beech tree.

00:50:34.280 --> 00:50:35.120 align:middle line:90%
That's a birch tree.

00:50:35.120 --> 00:50:35.920 align:middle line:90%
That's maple.

00:50:35.920 --> 00:50:37.730 align:middle line:90%
And it's not just that's maple.

00:50:37.730 --> 00:50:40.070 align:middle line:84%
That's maple, whom
all of my sugars

00:50:40.070 --> 00:50:43.040 align:middle line:84%
come from when I make my maple
syrup to provide all my sugar

00:50:43.040 --> 00:50:44.700 align:middle line:90%
resources for the year.

00:50:44.700 --> 00:50:45.500 align:middle line:90%
That's birch.

00:50:45.500 --> 00:50:47.600 align:middle line:84%
I extract a syrup
from that that I

00:50:47.600 --> 00:50:50.600 align:middle line:84%
use to marinate all my fish
in before I smoke them.

00:50:50.600 --> 00:50:53.090 align:middle line:84%
And I cut the twigs
to clean my teeth.

00:50:53.090 --> 00:50:55.550 align:middle line:84%
And it's a host to several
species of mushroom,

00:50:55.550 --> 00:50:57.240 align:middle line:90%
like chaga, that I work with.

00:50:57.240 --> 00:50:59.220 align:middle line:84%
So when I see birches,
it has meaning to me.

00:50:59.220 --> 00:51:01.680 align:middle line:84%
Its bark is the most flammable
thing on the landscape,

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:05.350 align:middle line:84%
so I use it as a fire
resource all winter long.

00:51:05.350 --> 00:51:07.100 align:middle line:84%
So when I see a birch
tree, it's not like,

00:51:07.100 --> 00:51:08.400 align:middle line:90%
oh, just a birch tree.

00:51:08.400 --> 00:51:12.050 align:middle line:84%
It has layers and
layers of meaning to me.

00:51:12.050 --> 00:51:13.910 align:middle line:84%
And then that's true
of the forbs around me,

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:16.250 align:middle line:84%
and the grasses around me,
and the species of animals

00:51:16.250 --> 00:51:17.720 align:middle line:90%
that I rely on for food.

00:51:17.720 --> 00:51:20.960 align:middle line:90%


00:51:20.960 --> 00:51:23.410 align:middle line:84%
It can be frustrating when
somebody says, oh my god, you'd

00:51:23.410 --> 00:51:24.210 align:middle line:90%
kill a bear.

00:51:24.210 --> 00:51:26.133 align:middle line:90%
That's just so horrible.

00:51:26.133 --> 00:51:27.050 align:middle line:90%
And it's like, really?

00:51:27.050 --> 00:51:30.020 align:middle line:84%
Because I can get
all my fat that I

00:51:30.020 --> 00:51:32.420 align:middle line:84%
cook with for the
whole year and probably

00:51:32.420 --> 00:51:35.750 align:middle line:84%
40 meals, which I will
share not just with myself,

00:51:35.750 --> 00:51:37.670 align:middle line:90%
but my wife, and my friends.

00:51:37.670 --> 00:51:39.080 align:middle line:90%
And my dog will eat that.

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:40.010 align:middle line:90%
I don't buy dog food.

00:51:40.010 --> 00:51:41.518 align:middle line:90%
I make all my dog food.

00:51:41.518 --> 00:51:43.560 align:middle line:84%
And somebody will tell
me, well, that's unethical

00:51:43.560 --> 00:51:44.090 align:middle line:90%
what you're doing.

00:51:44.090 --> 00:51:45.007 align:middle line:90%
And it's like, really?

00:51:45.007 --> 00:51:48.470 align:middle line:84%
Because if we actually looked at
the impacts of what I'm doing,

00:51:48.470 --> 00:51:51.230 align:middle line:84%
what one animal can
do in my household

00:51:51.230 --> 00:51:55.340 align:middle line:84%
versus the average person who
eats meat maybe and eats--

00:51:55.340 --> 00:51:57.950 align:middle line:84%
let's say they buy a cut of
meat, and it's from one animal.

00:51:57.950 --> 00:51:59.375 align:middle line:84%
And the next day, they
buy another cut of meat.

00:51:59.375 --> 00:52:00.417 align:middle line:90%
It's from another animal.

00:52:00.417 --> 00:52:04.760 align:middle line:84%
And they might eat actually
150 individuals, but only

00:52:04.760 --> 00:52:06.500 align:middle line:90%
one part of each one of them.

00:52:06.500 --> 00:52:09.690 align:middle line:84%
Whereas I'll eat the same
number of meals of meat,

00:52:09.690 --> 00:52:12.650 align:middle line:84%
but from one, or two,
or three animals.

00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:14.313 align:middle line:84%
It's interesting to
see the judgments

00:52:14.313 --> 00:52:15.980 align:middle line:84%
from people who don't
have relationships

00:52:15.980 --> 00:52:18.050 align:middle line:90%
to the natural world.

00:52:18.050 --> 00:52:21.900 align:middle line:84%
But also, it's like I was saying
before with the data points.

00:52:21.900 --> 00:52:25.120 align:middle line:84%
Each species that I know is
like another data point for me.

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:27.710 align:middle line:84%
It's something I can rely on,
someone I can reach out to

00:52:27.710 --> 00:52:28.650 align:middle line:90%
in a time of need.

00:52:28.650 --> 00:52:30.108 align:middle line:84%
So when I look out
at the landscape

00:52:30.108 --> 00:52:34.337 align:middle line:84%
and I see all these
individuals, I feel--

00:52:34.337 --> 00:52:36.420 align:middle line:84%
we talk about this thing
like the human condition.

00:52:36.420 --> 00:52:39.150 align:middle line:84%
That's relaxed in
me because I know

00:52:39.150 --> 00:52:44.670 align:middle line:84%
I am not an astronaut on a
foreign planet who's just

00:52:44.670 --> 00:52:47.190 align:middle line:84%
got this last bit of
air supply that I need

00:52:47.190 --> 00:52:48.570 align:middle line:90%
or I'm going to die.

00:52:48.570 --> 00:52:51.750 align:middle line:84%
I think that deep
inside people is a fear

00:52:51.750 --> 00:52:55.260 align:middle line:84%
that if the underpinnings
of their culture gave way,

00:52:55.260 --> 00:52:57.015 align:middle line:90%
they do not know how to be here.

00:52:57.015 --> 00:52:58.890 align:middle line:84%
I would feel that fear
if I was an astronaut.

00:52:58.890 --> 00:53:02.700 align:middle line:84%
If I was on the Moon or
Mars, I would feel like, wow,

00:53:02.700 --> 00:53:05.670 align:middle line:84%
if I didn't have all this
equipment or some of it fails,

00:53:05.670 --> 00:53:07.380 align:middle line:90%
I'm a dead man.

00:53:07.380 --> 00:53:11.170 align:middle line:84%
I need this to tether
me back to life.

00:53:11.170 --> 00:53:14.010 align:middle line:84%
And I think people feel like
that about their supermarkets,

00:53:14.010 --> 00:53:15.780 align:middle line:84%
and their equipment,
all that stuff

00:53:15.780 --> 00:53:17.710 align:middle line:84%
because they know they
don't know anything

00:53:17.710 --> 00:53:19.710 align:middle line:84%
about the natural world
or how to survive there.

00:53:19.710 --> 00:53:21.960 align:middle line:84%
That's why they consume so
many of those fake survival

00:53:21.960 --> 00:53:25.860 align:middle line:84%
shows, to see people who do,
and try to pick up tips, and OK.

00:53:25.860 --> 00:53:28.170 align:middle line:84%
And then they will spout
back these little fake facts

00:53:28.170 --> 00:53:30.210 align:middle line:84%
that they saw on
these survival shows.

00:53:30.210 --> 00:53:33.180 align:middle line:84%
It empowers them a little bit to
think they maybe got something

00:53:33.180 --> 00:53:34.620 align:middle line:90%
out of it.

00:53:34.620 --> 00:53:36.120 align:middle line:84%
But when you actually
do this stuff,

00:53:36.120 --> 00:53:38.490 align:middle line:84%
you develop these
meaningful relationships.

00:53:38.490 --> 00:53:39.840 align:middle line:90%
That eases inside you.

00:53:39.840 --> 00:53:44.490 align:middle line:84%
And you just know, I am
part of this natural world.

00:53:44.490 --> 00:53:45.497 align:middle line:90%
I know how to live here.

00:53:45.497 --> 00:53:47.580 align:middle line:84%
And it's not because I
think that something bad is

00:53:47.580 --> 00:53:49.300 align:middle line:90%
going to happen to our society.

00:53:49.300 --> 00:53:52.500 align:middle line:84%
It's because that's
in all of us.

00:53:52.500 --> 00:53:57.480 align:middle line:84%
We rely on the supply
that's handed down

00:53:57.480 --> 00:53:59.800 align:middle line:84%
through that hierarchy
we've been talking about.

00:53:59.800 --> 00:54:02.425 align:middle line:84%
And the fear that you could
be cut off lives in us.

00:54:02.425 --> 00:54:03.225 align:middle line:90%
So, yeah.

00:54:03.225 --> 00:54:04.920 align:middle line:84%
So I feel very
comfortable and relaxed.

00:54:04.920 --> 00:54:08.730 align:middle line:84%
And I think for people, if
they can go on a plant walk,

00:54:08.730 --> 00:54:10.890 align:middle line:84%
if they can learn to
make just a cup of tea

00:54:10.890 --> 00:54:13.812 align:middle line:84%
from something that grows around
them, that's how you start.

00:54:13.812 --> 00:54:15.270 align:middle line:84%
You don't start by
going, I'm going

00:54:15.270 --> 00:54:18.720 align:middle line:84%
to go out and do a moose
hunt or something like that.

00:54:18.720 --> 00:54:21.330 align:middle line:84%
Like, I'm going to buy a boat
and go lobstering or something

00:54:21.330 --> 00:54:22.130 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:54:22.130 --> 00:54:24.870 align:middle line:84%
It's like, OK, I'm going to
take some dandelion leaves

00:54:24.870 --> 00:54:27.700 align:middle line:84%
and make some tea that's going
to be good for my kidneys,

00:54:27.700 --> 00:54:29.880 align:middle line:84%
and it's going to be
good for my liver.

00:54:29.880 --> 00:54:31.950 align:middle line:84%
More than that, it's going
to be good for my soul

00:54:31.950 --> 00:54:34.260 align:middle line:84%
because I'm going to know
that I have just created

00:54:34.260 --> 00:54:35.880 align:middle line:90%
a relationship with a species.

00:54:35.880 --> 00:54:38.010 align:middle line:84%
And now every time
I see a dandelion,

00:54:38.010 --> 00:54:42.690 align:middle line:84%
it's more than just a yellow
blot on the landscape.

00:54:42.690 --> 00:54:46.980 align:middle line:84%
It's a friend of mine, and
I work with that friend.

00:54:46.980 --> 00:54:49.650 align:middle line:84%
And over time, when you
develop more and more of those,

00:54:49.650 --> 00:54:52.950 align:middle line:84%
eventually you've got
hundreds of creatures

00:54:52.950 --> 00:54:57.930 align:middle line:84%
that make up your actual body,
that make up your actual body.

00:54:57.930 --> 00:54:59.220 align:middle line:90%
You are made of them.

00:54:59.220 --> 00:55:01.543 align:middle line:84%
And then when people
criticize that it's like--

00:55:01.543 --> 00:55:04.200 align:middle line:84%
[SNORTS] --OK, man,
what are you made of?

00:55:04.200 --> 00:55:06.840 align:middle line:84%
Stuff from everywhere you
have no relationship to,

00:55:06.840 --> 00:55:08.820 align:middle line:90%
you don't even know what it is.

00:55:08.820 --> 00:55:10.300 align:middle line:84%
The average person,
for instance,

00:55:10.300 --> 00:55:13.440 align:middle line:84%
does not know even what
the foods that they eat

00:55:13.440 --> 00:55:16.390 align:middle line:84%
look like when they're
grown out half the time.

00:55:16.390 --> 00:55:18.673 align:middle line:84%
For instance, everybody
knows what asparagus

00:55:18.673 --> 00:55:20.340 align:middle line:84%
looks like when you
buy it in the store,

00:55:20.340 --> 00:55:22.650 align:middle line:84%
but most people wouldn't
recognize an adult asparagus

00:55:22.650 --> 00:55:23.790 align:middle line:90%
plant.

00:55:23.790 --> 00:55:25.457 align:middle line:84%
You could put them
right in front of it.

00:55:25.457 --> 00:55:26.290 align:middle line:90%
They would not know.

00:55:26.290 --> 00:55:28.082 align:middle line:84%
Most people don't know
what a lettuce looks

00:55:28.082 --> 00:55:29.370 align:middle line:90%
like unless they've grown it.

00:55:29.370 --> 00:55:31.870 align:middle line:84%
They don't know what it looks
like when it's gone to flower.

00:55:31.870 --> 00:55:33.670 align:middle line:84%
They've eaten it
their whole life.

00:55:33.670 --> 00:55:36.045 align:middle line:84%
And so it's really interesting
when you start, let's say,

00:55:36.045 --> 00:55:38.250 align:middle line:90%
fishing, and you harvest a--

00:55:38.250 --> 00:55:42.390 align:middle line:84%
I was cod fishing a
few days ago in Canada.

00:55:42.390 --> 00:55:43.390 align:middle line:90%
You bring up a cod fish.

00:55:43.390 --> 00:55:45.660 align:middle line:84%
And this is a fish that
you've grown up eating--

00:55:45.660 --> 00:55:46.890 align:middle line:90%
fish and chips.

00:55:46.890 --> 00:55:50.375 align:middle line:84%
Cod is a ubiquitous fish
people eat around the world,

00:55:50.375 --> 00:55:51.750 align:middle line:84%
but most people
couldn't tell you

00:55:51.750 --> 00:55:55.030 align:middle line:84%
what a cod fish looks like, even
though they've had it forever.

00:55:55.030 --> 00:55:56.500 align:middle line:90%
Most people have eaten it.

00:55:56.500 --> 00:55:59.008 align:middle line:84%
The McFish sandwich--
it's pollock.

00:55:59.008 --> 00:56:01.050 align:middle line:84%
Most people don't know
what a pollock looks like.

00:56:01.050 --> 00:56:02.508 align:middle line:84%
So it's really
interesting too when

00:56:02.508 --> 00:56:04.710 align:middle line:84%
you start to get back to
who these species are,

00:56:04.710 --> 00:56:06.090 align:middle line:90%
not just what they look like--

00:56:06.090 --> 00:56:10.230 align:middle line:84%
who they are, where they
live, how they behave.

00:56:10.230 --> 00:56:12.180 align:middle line:90%
And you become part of that.

00:56:12.180 --> 00:56:14.310 align:middle line:84%
At this point in
my life, I couldn't

00:56:14.310 --> 00:56:16.670 align:middle line:90%
imagine giving that up.

00:56:16.670 --> 00:56:19.310 align:middle line:90%
>> That's profound.

00:56:19.310 --> 00:56:20.285 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:56:20.285 --> 00:56:23.210 align:middle line:84%
I feel like you've given
a lot here, Daniel.

00:56:23.210 --> 00:56:25.760 align:middle line:84%
And I feel that through
your explanation,

00:56:25.760 --> 00:56:28.100 align:middle line:84%
you're leading by
example in terms

00:56:28.100 --> 00:56:30.200 align:middle line:84%
of how people can rewild
themselves and experience

00:56:30.200 --> 00:56:33.860 align:middle line:84%
more peace to ease the
condition of being human.

00:56:33.860 --> 00:56:36.890 align:middle line:84%
And I see it in Vanuatu as well
with the Indigenous people.

00:56:36.890 --> 00:56:39.440 align:middle line:84%
They're happy and connected
because every day they're

00:56:39.440 --> 00:56:41.480 align:middle line:90%
in communion with nature.

00:56:41.480 --> 00:56:45.470 align:middle line:84%
And we've taken that away
from most of our lives.

00:56:45.470 --> 00:56:47.720 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if there's anything
you want to finalize on

00:56:47.720 --> 00:56:49.795 align:middle line:84%
or any thoughts
you want to leave--

00:56:49.795 --> 00:56:50.440 align:middle line:84%
>> I know you're
going to edit it,

00:56:50.440 --> 00:56:52.315 align:middle line:84%
so I just want to say
this to you about that,

00:56:52.315 --> 00:56:55.225 align:middle line:84%
is that the big
difference is that, again,

00:56:55.225 --> 00:56:56.600 align:middle line:84%
I'm approaching
it as a practice,

00:56:56.600 --> 00:56:58.410 align:middle line:84%
and they're coming out
of a lineage of it.

00:56:58.410 --> 00:57:03.120 align:middle line:84%
And I'll never be able to
gather that much information,

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:05.790 align:middle line:84%
as much as that they hold
about their landscape.

00:57:05.790 --> 00:57:09.180 align:middle line:84%
But also, I'm an
orphan, and they're not.

00:57:09.180 --> 00:57:13.980 align:middle line:84%
Because I don't know where my
lineage even comes from because

00:57:13.980 --> 00:57:15.700 align:middle line:90%
there was a break in it.

00:57:15.700 --> 00:57:18.000 align:middle line:90%
And most of us are orphans.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:19.440 align:middle line:90%
So we don't know our people.

00:57:19.440 --> 00:57:21.623 align:middle line:84%
We don't say-- you don't
come here and-- oh,

00:57:21.623 --> 00:57:23.290 align:middle line:84%
you tell me about
your mom and your dad,

00:57:23.290 --> 00:57:24.080 align:middle line:90%
and then all the way--

00:57:24.080 --> 00:57:26.038 align:middle line:84%
yeah, and we trace our
lineage all the way back

00:57:26.038 --> 00:57:27.240 align:middle line:90%
to the first people.

00:57:27.240 --> 00:57:29.760 align:middle line:84%
Because most
hunter-gatherers believe

00:57:29.760 --> 00:57:31.470 align:middle line:84%
that they can
trace their lineage

00:57:31.470 --> 00:57:33.630 align:middle line:90%
back to the first humans.

00:57:33.630 --> 00:57:36.540 align:middle line:84%
That's one of those
ubiquitous things,

00:57:36.540 --> 00:57:38.590 align:middle line:84%
like, well, we're
the real people.

00:57:38.590 --> 00:57:41.790 align:middle line:84%
A lot of tribes' name
translates to the real people,

00:57:41.790 --> 00:57:45.330 align:middle line:84%
the real ones, or the
right people, or whatever.

00:57:45.330 --> 00:57:50.040 align:middle line:84%
We, most of us, can go like, oh,
well, I'm from sort of England.

00:57:50.040 --> 00:57:52.158 align:middle line:84%
Most of us can only
go back so far.

00:57:52.158 --> 00:57:53.700 align:middle line:84%
And there was a
break somewhere where

00:57:53.700 --> 00:57:55.980 align:middle line:90%
our people were separated.

00:57:55.980 --> 00:57:58.500 align:middle line:84%
That's a big part of the
domestication process.

00:57:58.500 --> 00:58:01.230 align:middle line:84%
Your dog does not know
it was a gray wolf.

00:58:01.230 --> 00:58:03.150 align:middle line:84%
We can't trace back
to Indigenous people,

00:58:03.150 --> 00:58:07.320 align:middle line:84%
so all I can do is
piece together the best

00:58:07.320 --> 00:58:10.650 align:middle line:90%
mosaic that I can right now.

00:58:10.650 --> 00:58:12.870 align:middle line:84%
Those last Indigenous
people are really important.

00:58:12.870 --> 00:58:14.600 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they're really,
really important.

00:58:14.600 --> 00:58:16.740 align:middle line:84%
Because if we lost
every dog on the planet,

00:58:16.740 --> 00:58:19.770 align:middle line:84%
we can just get gray wolves
and turn them into dogs again.

00:58:19.770 --> 00:58:22.080 align:middle line:84%
We're going to lose the
last Indigenous people.

00:58:22.080 --> 00:58:24.693 align:middle line:84%
All that's left are going to
be domesticated orphan people.

00:58:24.693 --> 00:58:26.110 align:middle line:84%
That's a really
scary thing to me.

00:58:26.110 --> 00:58:27.550 align:middle line:90%
So it's like--

00:58:27.550 --> 00:58:28.350 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:58:28.350 --> 00:58:32.980 align:middle line:84%
At this point, we actually
are starting over in a way.

00:58:32.980 --> 00:58:35.440 align:middle line:84%
And this practice that I'm
doing is like a starting over.

00:58:35.440 --> 00:58:37.690 align:middle line:84%
And I hope I can share
it with more people

00:58:37.690 --> 00:58:41.170 align:middle line:84%
because we absolutely
need this going forward.

00:58:41.170 --> 00:58:44.080 align:middle line:90%
I mean, we can't--

00:58:44.080 --> 00:58:45.940 align:middle line:90%
this can only go on so long.

00:58:45.940 --> 00:58:48.040 align:middle line:84%
Like if something's
not sustainable, well,

00:58:48.040 --> 00:58:48.970 align:middle line:90%
then that's it.

00:58:48.970 --> 00:58:50.620 align:middle line:90%
Why even keep doing it?

00:58:50.620 --> 00:58:52.570 align:middle line:84%
It's like, we know it
can't be sustained.

00:58:52.570 --> 00:58:54.315 align:middle line:84%
We have to do
something different.

00:58:54.315 --> 00:58:55.690 align:middle line:84%
And even if this
is only a piece,

00:58:55.690 --> 00:58:57.640 align:middle line:84%
this is the piece
that I'm taking up.

00:58:57.640 --> 00:59:00.880 align:middle line:84%
And I want to share it because
this has to be kept alive.

00:59:00.880 --> 00:59:04.390 align:middle line:84%
If we're going to have
baseball hall of fame museums

00:59:04.390 --> 00:59:06.755 align:middle line:84%
and not have any museums
dedicated to this,

00:59:06.755 --> 00:59:07.630 align:middle line:90%
you know what I mean?

00:59:07.630 --> 00:59:10.030 align:middle line:84%
This should be kept alive,
even if it's a museum thing.

00:59:10.030 --> 00:59:13.000 align:middle line:84%
If there's going to be
renaissance fairs and civil war

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:15.250 align:middle line:84%
reenactments, and
nobody's reenacting

00:59:15.250 --> 00:59:17.720 align:middle line:84%
the life of living on the
landscape, that makes no sense.

00:59:17.720 --> 00:59:18.520 align:middle line:90%
That's our way.

00:59:18.520 --> 00:59:19.855 align:middle line:90%
So that's what I'm doing.

00:59:19.855 --> 00:59:21.730 align:middle line:84%
I know it pales to what
you're talking about,

00:59:21.730 --> 00:59:22.605 align:middle line:90%
the people out there.

00:59:22.605 --> 00:59:23.840 align:middle line:90%
I'll never have that.

00:59:23.840 --> 00:59:25.480 align:middle line:84%
But what I have
is enough for me.

00:59:25.480 --> 00:59:26.840 align:middle line:90%
It's really satisfying.

